00:03:07.550 --> 00:03:10.520
So looking back to look forward.

00:03:10.520 --> 00:03:14.330
The anniversary
commemorates the founding

00:03:14.330 --> 00:03:19.220
in 1943 of Radcliffe College's
Women's Rights Collection,

00:03:19.220 --> 00:03:22.790
which then consisted of about
30 cartons of manuscripts

00:03:22.790 --> 00:03:26.000
and several hundred
printed volumes.

00:03:26.000 --> 00:03:28.040
The Women's Rights
Collection came out

00:03:28.040 --> 00:03:31.610
of what has come to be
known as the first wave

00:03:31.610 --> 00:03:35.270
of American feminism,
the decades of activism

00:03:35.270 --> 00:03:38.060
from the second quarter
of the 19th century

00:03:38.060 --> 00:03:40.970
into the early decades
of the 20th, which

00:03:40.970 --> 00:03:44.960
culminated in the 1920s
passage of the 19th Amendment

00:03:44.960 --> 00:03:47.960
to the US Constitution,
declaring that the right

00:03:47.960 --> 00:03:51.590
to vote in the United States
could not be abridged by sex.

00:03:51.590 --> 00:03:53.690
The amendment, of
course, enfranchised

00:03:53.690 --> 00:03:57.320
only those American women
who were not already

00:03:57.320 --> 00:04:00.180
denied the vote
by virtue of race,

00:04:00.180 --> 00:04:03.650
national origin, territorial
residence, disability,

00:04:03.650 --> 00:04:06.470
and other qualifiers.

00:04:06.470 --> 00:04:10.430
By the 1950s, Schlesinger's
women's suffrage collections

00:04:10.430 --> 00:04:12.770
were very strong,
nearly peerless.

00:04:12.770 --> 00:04:16.790
Only Sophia Smith's special
collections could rival them.

00:04:16.790 --> 00:04:19.550
But the library
grew quite slowly

00:04:19.550 --> 00:04:23.300
until the gathering of a second
wave of American feminism

00:04:23.300 --> 00:04:25.940
beginning in the 1960s.

00:04:25.940 --> 00:04:29.090
The thinkers, activists,
and organizations

00:04:29.090 --> 00:04:31.730
of the second wave
wanted to be sure

00:04:31.730 --> 00:04:33.650
that their legacies
would be preserved

00:04:33.650 --> 00:04:36.110
in libraries and in archives.

00:04:36.110 --> 00:04:40.160
And many of them joined
forces with Schlesinger.

00:04:40.160 --> 00:04:43.910
Our second-wave collections
span and sometimes

00:04:43.910 --> 00:04:46.790
bridge the many
schisms of that era.

00:04:46.790 --> 00:04:49.970
We include the papers of
liberal and radical feminists,

00:04:49.970 --> 00:04:52.670
of white and
African-American activists,

00:04:52.670 --> 00:04:56.930
of queer and straight thinkers,
of anti-pornography and pro-sex

00:04:56.930 --> 00:04:59.150
feminists, and so on.

00:04:59.150 --> 00:05:02.960
So we hold, to name just a few,
the papers of Betty Friedan,

00:05:02.960 --> 00:05:05.090
of Susan Brownmiller,
of Adrienne Rich,

00:05:05.090 --> 00:05:08.960
of June Jordan, Andrea Dworkin,
Catharine MacKinnon, Florence

00:05:08.960 --> 00:05:12.530
Kennedy, and as of last
January, Angela Davis,

00:05:12.530 --> 00:05:15.560
as well as the organizational
records of NOW and NOW

00:05:15.560 --> 00:05:18.230
Legal Defense and
Education Fund, of Women

00:05:18.230 --> 00:05:22.670
Against Pornography, and of
the Boston Women's Health Book

00:05:22.670 --> 00:05:24.380
Collective.

00:05:24.380 --> 00:05:27.260
For several decades
now, scholars

00:05:27.260 --> 00:05:28.850
of the history of
women and gender

00:05:28.850 --> 00:05:32.780
have questioned the very
idea of feminist waves, which

00:05:32.780 --> 00:05:36.560
have never been as unified
or as discrete or as clear

00:05:36.560 --> 00:05:41.550
in their swelling and breaking
as the wave metaphor suggests.

00:05:41.550 --> 00:05:44.540
Nonetheless, it's been
obvious for some time

00:05:44.540 --> 00:05:47.870
that the so-called
second wave is over,

00:05:47.870 --> 00:05:51.980
having reached its sell-by
date long before the 2016

00:05:51.980 --> 00:05:54.450
presidential election.

00:05:54.450 --> 00:05:58.080
Through its strengths
and its faults,

00:05:58.080 --> 00:06:00.870
the second wave has
given rise or given way

00:06:00.870 --> 00:06:04.740
to subsequent forms
of feminist activism.

00:06:04.740 --> 00:06:09.210
Today's emerging feminists, the
fourth or maybe the fifth wave

00:06:09.210 --> 00:06:13.620
by some reckonings, have fresh
energies and different ways

00:06:13.620 --> 00:06:18.220
of viewing the world than their
predecessors sometimes did.

00:06:18.220 --> 00:06:20.950
Their intellectual and
institutional relationships

00:06:20.950 --> 00:06:23.380
to those predecessors
is, I think

00:06:23.380 --> 00:06:28.630
it's safe to say, mixed, a
blend of homage and critique

00:06:28.630 --> 00:06:32.650
that any movement
needs to remain vital.

00:06:32.650 --> 00:06:35.680
The commitments,
priorities, hopes and fears

00:06:35.680 --> 00:06:39.590
of millennial feminists and
their links to the commitments,

00:06:39.590 --> 00:06:44.050
priorities, hopes and fears
of the second wave and indeed

00:06:44.050 --> 00:06:48.490
the first, are our subject
here this afternoon.

00:06:48.490 --> 00:06:51.490
What batons have
been passed and which

00:06:51.490 --> 00:06:54.610
have been dropped
between the generations?

00:06:54.610 --> 00:06:57.190
How have rising
feminists shined light

00:06:57.190 --> 00:07:00.370
into the blind spots
of their forebears.

00:07:00.370 --> 00:07:05.140
And also in turn, what did the
instigators of the second wave

00:07:05.140 --> 00:07:09.850
know that we may be at
risk of forgetting today?

00:07:09.850 --> 00:07:14.070
As we turn toward another
important moment for women,

00:07:14.070 --> 00:07:17.140
for voters to use or
lose the franchise

00:07:17.140 --> 00:07:20.140
and the rights that go
with it, and as libraries

00:07:20.140 --> 00:07:23.980
like ours begin to collect
the records of Gen Y

00:07:23.980 --> 00:07:27.520
and of millennials, getting
a handle on these questions

00:07:27.520 --> 00:07:30.840
seem important.

00:07:30.840 --> 00:07:33.030
Populating and framing
today's discussion

00:07:33.030 --> 00:07:34.950
came out of a team
effort, as Tomiko

00:07:34.950 --> 00:07:38.700
said, between a classically
second-wave organization

00:07:38.700 --> 00:07:40.290
and a millennial one.

00:07:40.290 --> 00:07:43.710
Schlesinger Library and the
New York-based nonprofit VIDA,

00:07:43.710 --> 00:07:45.990
Women and the Literary Arts.

00:07:45.990 --> 00:07:48.240
VIDA is a feminist
organization committed

00:07:48.240 --> 00:07:51.690
to creating transparency
around the lack of gender

00:07:51.690 --> 00:07:55.050
parity in the literary
landscape and to amplifying

00:07:55.050 --> 00:07:57.780
historically marginalized
voices, including people

00:07:57.780 --> 00:08:00.270
of color, writers
with disability,

00:08:00.270 --> 00:08:04.590
and queer, trans, and gender
non-conforming individuals.

00:08:04.590 --> 00:08:06.870
The VIDA Count, VIDA's
flagship program,

00:08:06.870 --> 00:08:09.000
now marking its
10th anniversary,

00:08:09.000 --> 00:08:11.460
highlights gender
imbalances in publishing

00:08:11.460 --> 00:08:15.030
by tallying genre, book
reviewers, books reviewed,

00:08:15.030 --> 00:08:18.960
and journalistic bylines to
offer a data-driven assessment

00:08:18.960 --> 00:08:21.060
of the publishing world.

00:08:21.060 --> 00:08:24.150
Through the VIDA Count, along
with the online publication

00:08:24.150 --> 00:08:28.440
of VIDA Review and
initiatives like #saferlit,

00:08:28.440 --> 00:08:31.380
VIDA aims to stimulate
thoughtful conversation

00:08:31.380 --> 00:08:35.039
about the challenges faced
by marginalized populations

00:08:35.039 --> 00:08:38.730
within the literary community
and beyond with hopes

00:08:38.730 --> 00:08:42.510
of enabling a more
inclusive literary culture.

00:08:42.510 --> 00:08:45.700
In recent years, VIDA has
added race, disability,

00:08:45.700 --> 00:08:49.770
sexual identity, and age
to the categories counted.

00:08:49.770 --> 00:08:52.050
The count has been
widely acknowledged

00:08:52.050 --> 00:08:54.840
by myriad national
news outlets as one

00:08:54.840 --> 00:08:56.970
of the only and most
reliable sources

00:08:56.970 --> 00:08:59.940
on gender disparity
in the literary world.

00:08:59.940 --> 00:09:04.590
It has also moved the needle
on many important publications,

00:09:04.590 --> 00:09:08.200
except those which are
unrepentant resisters.

00:09:08.200 --> 00:09:10.980
[LAUGHTER]

00:09:10.980 --> 00:09:15.000
The men's review of books,
as I like to call it.

00:09:15.000 --> 00:09:17.910
I want to thank VIDA board
members Melissa Febos

00:09:17.910 --> 00:09:21.270
and Hafizah Geter for their
help curating this stellar group

00:09:21.270 --> 00:09:22.350
of panelists.

00:09:22.350 --> 00:09:24.720
I'll introduce them
all now in the order

00:09:24.720 --> 00:09:27.180
in which they'll speak.

00:09:27.180 --> 00:09:30.540
So first up will be the
poet Fatimah Asghar,

00:09:30.540 --> 00:09:33.450
the writer and
co-creator of Brown Girls

00:09:33.450 --> 00:09:36.660
an Emmy-nominated web series
centered on friendships

00:09:36.660 --> 00:09:39.750
between women of color,
which is in development

00:09:39.750 --> 00:09:42.510
for television with HBO.

00:09:42.510 --> 00:09:46.760
Asghar's debut collection of
poems, If They Come For Us,

00:09:46.760 --> 00:09:50.880
which she has a copy of
in front of her right now,

00:09:50.880 --> 00:09:54.960
was published by the One
World imprint of Random House

00:09:54.960 --> 00:09:56.460
just last month.

00:09:56.460 --> 00:09:59.100
It explores her
unique subjectivity

00:09:59.100 --> 00:10:03.930
as a Pakistani Muslim American
at times of peril and fracture

00:10:03.930 --> 00:10:07.860
in her home country, especially
around the time of partition,

00:10:07.860 --> 00:10:10.410
and in today's United States.

00:10:10.410 --> 00:10:12.570
Starred reviews in
Publishers Weekly

00:10:12.570 --> 00:10:15.180
and in the Library
Journal hail her voice

00:10:15.180 --> 00:10:19.110
as at once fierce and
tender, personal, powerful,

00:10:19.110 --> 00:10:20.730
and political.

00:10:20.730 --> 00:10:23.730
She is also a graduate of
Cambridge Rindge and Latin High

00:10:23.730 --> 00:10:24.270
School.

00:10:24.270 --> 00:10:27.090
[APPLAUSE]

00:10:27.090 --> 00:10:29.310
Some of whose
students and faculty

00:10:29.310 --> 00:10:33.180
are here today to
hear and pay tribute

00:10:33.180 --> 00:10:35.790
to their famous forebear.

00:10:35.790 --> 00:10:38.040
Writer and legal
activist Dana Bolger

00:10:38.040 --> 00:10:39.990
is co-founder of
the organization

00:10:39.990 --> 00:10:43.350
Know Your IX, a national
youth-led movement

00:10:43.350 --> 00:10:45.240
that educates and
empowers students

00:10:45.240 --> 00:10:48.840
to end gender violence in
their schools and beyond.

00:10:48.840 --> 00:10:52.440
Founded in 2013, Know Your
IX works with high school

00:10:52.440 --> 00:10:54.000
and with college
students, training

00:10:54.000 --> 00:10:56.580
them to combat gender
discrimination, including

00:10:56.580 --> 00:10:58.140
sexual violence.

00:10:58.140 --> 00:11:00.690
Bolger also serves
as a senior editor

00:11:00.690 --> 00:11:03.600
at Feministing, a leading
online community run

00:11:03.600 --> 00:11:06.000
by and for young feminists.

00:11:06.000 --> 00:11:07.800
She has testified
before Congress

00:11:07.800 --> 00:11:11.130
on sexual assault policy
and legislative reform.

00:11:11.130 --> 00:11:13.260
And her writing has
appeared in the New York

00:11:13.260 --> 00:11:16.020
Times, the Washington Post,
and The Wall Street Journal,

00:11:16.020 --> 00:11:18.780
among other outlets.

00:11:18.780 --> 00:11:20.940
Melissa Febos,
assistant professor

00:11:20.940 --> 00:11:23.460
of creative writing at
Monmouth University,

00:11:23.460 --> 00:11:26.310
is the author of the memoir
Whip Smart, published

00:11:26.310 --> 00:11:30.030
in 2010, and the essay
collection Abandon Me,

00:11:30.030 --> 00:11:34.410
published in 2017, which the
New Yorker called "mesmerizing,"

00:11:34.410 --> 00:11:38.400
and which was a Lambda Literary
Award finalist, a Triangle

00:11:38.400 --> 00:11:41.190
Publishing Award
finalist, an Indie Next

00:11:41.190 --> 00:11:44.580
pick, and a named
best book of 2017

00:11:44.580 --> 00:11:47.200
by an astonishing
range of publications,

00:11:47.200 --> 00:11:50.580
including Esquire, Book Riot,
The Cut, Electric Literature,

00:11:50.580 --> 00:11:53.460
The Brooklyn Rail,
Bustle, Refinery29, Salon,

00:11:53.460 --> 00:11:54.270
and The Rumpus.

00:11:54.270 --> 00:11:56.103
I don't think there are
many people who have

00:11:56.103 --> 00:11:59.100
reached Esquire and The Rumpus.

00:11:59.100 --> 00:12:02.670
The inaugural winner of the
Jeanne Cordova Nonfiction

00:12:02.670 --> 00:12:04.860
Prize from Lambda
Literary, Febos

00:12:04.860 --> 00:12:07.980
will publish a second
essay collection, Girlhood,

00:12:07.980 --> 00:12:11.500
with Bloomsbury in 2020.

00:12:11.500 --> 00:12:14.660
A cultural critic,
Kim Foster founded

00:12:14.660 --> 00:12:19.910
For Harriet, an online community
of women of African ancestry,

00:12:19.910 --> 00:12:23.360
founded it back in 2010 while
she was an undergraduate right

00:12:23.360 --> 00:12:25.250
here at Harvard.

00:12:25.250 --> 00:12:27.990
Welcome back, Kim.

00:12:27.990 --> 00:12:31.880
For Harriet has since seeded
three sister sites, Soar,

00:12:31.880 --> 00:12:34.100
Shine, and The Culture.

00:12:34.100 --> 00:12:36.350
The aim of these
communities is, quote,

00:12:36.350 --> 00:12:40.320
"to raise the level of discourse
surrounding black womanhood."

00:12:40.320 --> 00:12:43.100
The For Harriet sites
have become premier spaces

00:12:43.100 --> 00:12:46.107
for black women's
journalism and storytelling

00:12:46.107 --> 00:12:47.690
and have been featured
in the New York

00:12:47.690 --> 00:12:50.780
Times and other
national media outlets.

00:12:50.780 --> 00:12:53.090
Kim has written for The
Guardian and for Newsweek

00:12:53.090 --> 00:12:56.690
and has appeared widely
on television and radio.

00:12:56.690 --> 00:12:59.780
Two years ago, Forbes
magazine named Foster

00:12:59.780 --> 00:13:03.780
to its national
30 under 30 list.

00:13:03.780 --> 00:13:06.950
Finally, Emi Koiama,
activist, writer,

00:13:06.950 --> 00:13:09.680
and self-described
rogue intellectual,

00:13:09.680 --> 00:13:13.130
is the author of the pioneering
Transfeminist Manifesto

00:13:13.130 --> 00:13:16.280
and other essays of
transfeminism, published back

00:13:16.280 --> 00:13:17.550
in 1999.

00:13:17.550 --> 00:13:20.900
This is very early for
transfeminist writing.

00:13:20.900 --> 00:13:24.620
The Manifesto has circulated
both as an underground text

00:13:24.620 --> 00:13:28.620
and in published versions
for nearly two decades.

00:13:28.620 --> 00:13:30.470
We have become
increasingly aware

00:13:30.470 --> 00:13:34.630
that the diversity of women is
our strength, not our weakness,

00:13:34.630 --> 00:13:37.460
Koiama writes in that manifesto.

00:13:37.460 --> 00:13:40.010
Koiama's transfeminism
and her activism

00:13:40.010 --> 00:13:43.970
more broadly embraces what
she calls feminist coalition

00:13:43.970 --> 00:13:47.060
projects in which women
from different backgrounds

00:13:47.060 --> 00:13:49.790
stand up for each other.

00:13:49.790 --> 00:13:52.790
Koiama is a multi-issue
social justice activist,

00:13:52.790 --> 00:13:56.720
synthesizing feminist,
Asian, survivor, dyke, queer,

00:13:56.720 --> 00:13:58.670
sex worker, intersect,
genderqueer,

00:13:58.670 --> 00:14:00.890
and [? crypt ?] politics.

00:14:00.890 --> 00:14:03.500
When I asked her about her
pronoun preferences for this

00:14:03.500 --> 00:14:06.740
introduction, she wrote, and I
quote-- and she said I could--

00:14:06.740 --> 00:14:08.990
"I don't subscribe to
the neoliberal politics

00:14:08.990 --> 00:14:11.060
