00:16:04.680 --> 00:16:10.170
"I see my not-me on the news,
she who weds for her sweet 16.

00:16:10.170 --> 00:16:12.470
Mosquito bites for breasts.

00:16:12.470 --> 00:16:16.140
My not-khaala's trace her
hands with mehndi, a plate

00:16:16.140 --> 00:16:18.660
of mathai bursting at her feet.

00:16:18.660 --> 00:16:24.860
My not-khalu's dance pound palm
to drum, stave off monsoons.

00:16:24.860 --> 00:16:27.120
My not-abbu checks the
sheets for her blood

00:16:27.120 --> 00:16:31.270
the morning after, brandishes
the satin like a flag,

00:16:31.270 --> 00:16:34.440
his pride singing
through the town.

00:16:34.440 --> 00:16:37.200
There is my not-me
again, the one I

00:16:37.200 --> 00:16:41.580
could have been, drowned in a
burqa on her way to the market,

00:16:41.580 --> 00:16:43.890
fingering mangoes
through gloves,

00:16:43.890 --> 00:16:46.770
nihari steaming for
hours at the flat shared

00:16:46.770 --> 00:16:49.260
with my not-husband's family.

00:16:49.260 --> 00:16:52.470
My not-me's eyes,
brilliant and green,

00:16:52.470 --> 00:16:55.630
decorating the pages
of Western magazines,

00:16:55.630 --> 00:16:59.630
eyes that earn a white man
awards and showings, but eyes

00:16:59.630 --> 00:17:01.860
that stay [INAUDIBLE]
in the mountains

00:17:01.860 --> 00:17:05.280
while my not-me rims her
son's mouth with salt to trick

00:17:05.280 --> 00:17:07.680
his belly into not hunger.

00:17:07.680 --> 00:17:10.589
My not-me celebrating
Diwali, lights

00:17:10.589 --> 00:17:12.950
gathered at the
base of her door.

00:17:12.950 --> 00:17:17.280
My not-me Indian worshipping
a host of different gods,

00:17:17.280 --> 00:17:19.190
calling all their names.

00:17:19.190 --> 00:17:24.150
My not-tongue not foreign,
not accented, not strange.

00:17:24.150 --> 00:17:26.849
My not-me not worried
about Taliban,

00:17:26.849 --> 00:17:29.080
but still worried about men.

00:17:29.080 --> 00:17:32.600
My not-me on the bus,
divided among the passengers

00:17:32.600 --> 00:17:36.960
hands, abdomen gutted,
left on a road to die.

00:17:36.960 --> 00:17:41.160
Still not me alone and not me."

00:17:43.760 --> 00:17:47.630
So I think that when
I think about feminism

00:17:47.630 --> 00:17:51.110
and how it relates to my
work, I think about the ways

00:17:51.110 --> 00:17:54.740
that my work tries
really hard to grapple

00:17:54.740 --> 00:17:56.450
a lot with
intersectional identity

00:17:56.450 --> 00:18:00.770
and giving the space to
have a full breadth of one's

00:18:00.770 --> 00:18:04.370
humanity, which I think is
sometimes really difficult when

00:18:04.370 --> 00:18:08.540
you're a person who comes from
a background or backgrounds that

00:18:08.540 --> 00:18:10.970
are intersecting and
when people kind of try

00:18:10.970 --> 00:18:14.090
to categorize or pigeon-hole
you into being one thing

00:18:14.090 --> 00:18:17.060
and don't really allow
you the space of really

00:18:17.060 --> 00:18:19.550
being a full human.

00:18:19.550 --> 00:18:21.980
And thinking about, too--
so I work as a poet,

00:18:21.980 --> 00:18:23.180
and I'm also a screenwriter.

00:18:23.180 --> 00:18:25.100
And I think a lot
about the way that we

00:18:25.100 --> 00:18:27.110
develop characters in screen.

00:18:27.110 --> 00:18:29.750
And a lot of times the way that
folks talk about developing

00:18:29.750 --> 00:18:32.340
characters is they'll be like,
well, here's a character.

00:18:32.340 --> 00:18:33.470
This is their backgrounds.

00:18:33.470 --> 00:18:34.970
These are the issues
that they face.

00:18:34.970 --> 00:18:37.370
And this is that, which
to me always rings

00:18:37.370 --> 00:18:40.070
super hollow when you
then go to screen and see

00:18:40.070 --> 00:18:42.320
that kind of beings displayed.

00:18:42.320 --> 00:18:46.250
The reason why is it doesn't
give space for humanity.

00:18:46.250 --> 00:18:47.630
It doesn't give
space for someone

00:18:47.630 --> 00:18:50.720
to just be a full person.

00:18:50.720 --> 00:18:52.250
And I think sometimes
when I think

00:18:52.250 --> 00:18:54.710
about the danger of when we
talk about representation,

00:18:54.710 --> 00:18:56.730
especially when we
talk about filmmaking

00:18:56.730 --> 00:18:59.480
or when we talk about poetry
and we talk about art,

00:18:59.480 --> 00:19:01.910
is when you talk
about representation

00:19:01.910 --> 00:19:04.790
and you kind of reduce it
down to just that and you

00:19:04.790 --> 00:19:08.390
don't allow for the reasons
why representation is important

00:19:08.390 --> 00:19:12.419
and the reasons why it's
important to have people who

00:19:12.419 --> 00:19:14.210
come from the backgrounds
of the characters

00:19:14.210 --> 00:19:16.043
that they're writing
write those backgrounds

00:19:16.043 --> 00:19:18.170
and to kind of give
them that fullness

00:19:18.170 --> 00:19:21.939
and that sense of complexity
that sometimes missing.

00:19:21.939 --> 00:19:24.230
So I think that it's interesting
because a lot of times

00:19:24.230 --> 00:19:26.990
I'm asked about things
about representation.

00:19:26.990 --> 00:19:29.684
And it's hard, because I think
representation is really,

00:19:29.684 --> 00:19:31.100
really important,
but I also think

00:19:31.100 --> 00:19:33.530
it's a really hollow
concept when you just

00:19:33.530 --> 00:19:37.790
treat it as representation
for representation's sake.

00:19:37.790 --> 00:19:38.900
And so I really want to--

00:19:38.900 --> 00:19:41.300
I think for me the thing
that really matters to me,

00:19:41.300 --> 00:19:43.820
the thing that drives
a lot of my work,

00:19:43.820 --> 00:19:46.580
is to really focus
in on the human

00:19:46.580 --> 00:19:49.130
and thinking about
the pain and the joy

00:19:49.130 --> 00:19:51.680
and the love of all
of those identities.

00:19:51.680 --> 00:19:53.330
And I think for
so many of us who

00:19:53.330 --> 00:19:55.130
come from marginalized
backgrounds,

00:19:55.130 --> 00:19:58.100
we kind of come from this space
where people only talk about

00:19:58.100 --> 00:20:02.840
your identity as a space of
trauma and as a space of pain

00:20:02.840 --> 00:20:07.010
and of sadness and as a
lack, like you are this

00:20:07.010 --> 00:20:08.390
because you lack whiteness.

00:20:08.390 --> 00:20:10.310
You are this because
you lack maleness.

00:20:10.310 --> 00:20:14.810
You are this because you lack
straightness, whatever that is.

00:20:14.810 --> 00:20:17.420
And that's a really damaging
way of thinking about identity.

00:20:17.420 --> 00:20:19.550
And it's a really,
really damaging thing

00:20:19.550 --> 00:20:23.910
to be a person of color, to
be a woman of color, a queer

00:20:23.910 --> 00:20:25.880
woman of color, and
have to kind of think

00:20:25.880 --> 00:20:32.000
about yourself as a lack and
not from a positive [? sight. ?]

00:20:32.000 --> 00:20:34.870
And so something that I
think about in my work

00:20:34.870 --> 00:20:37.550
is to really not
let that happen,

00:20:37.550 --> 00:20:40.010
to really not say that
I come from a lack

00:20:40.010 --> 00:20:42.860
or I'm a lack of something but
that I'm actually a positive.

00:20:42.860 --> 00:20:45.410
I exist in this positive space.

00:20:45.410 --> 00:20:48.176
And that's not to say that
you can't you talk about pain.

00:20:48.176 --> 00:20:50.300
That poem that I just read
had a lot of pain in it.

00:20:50.300 --> 00:20:53.780
But thinking about what are the
complicated bonds of sisterhood

00:20:53.780 --> 00:20:58.640
and intimacy formed from some
of these backgrounds and how

00:20:58.640 --> 00:21:00.990
are those terrains
of joy and of love.

00:21:00.990 --> 00:21:03.122
And how is that a specific
kind of love and joy

00:21:03.122 --> 00:21:04.580
that other people
don't have access

00:21:04.580 --> 00:21:07.370
to that we can celebrate?

00:21:07.370 --> 00:21:12.050
So I'm going to read
another poem, which

00:21:12.050 --> 00:21:15.530
is a poem that I wrote.

00:21:15.530 --> 00:21:20.840
I did crew here on
the Charles River.

00:21:20.840 --> 00:21:23.570
And this is a poem for the
people that I did crew with.

00:21:23.570 --> 00:21:27.610
And it's called "To
Prevent Hypothermia."

00:21:27.610 --> 00:21:31.090
"After the race, my teammates
kicked the boys off the bus

00:21:31.090 --> 00:21:34.060
and into the downpour,
blocked the windows

00:21:34.060 --> 00:21:38.440
with their sweatshirts, peeled
the wet clothes from my skin,

00:21:38.440 --> 00:21:42.430
each inch matted down,
disobedient, hair

00:21:42.430 --> 00:21:44.820
plastered to my brown legs.

00:21:44.820 --> 00:21:48.010
It took two hungry girls
to remove the Spandex

00:21:48.010 --> 00:21:51.520
from my paling thighs,
their blond hair a cascade

00:21:51.520 --> 00:21:55.240
from heaven, water droplets
falling from their roots,

00:21:55.240 --> 00:21:57.160
stinging my body.

00:21:57.160 --> 00:22:00.900
The ports tore off my
shirts and sports bra.

00:22:00.900 --> 00:22:04.150
And my nipples lighthouses
in a swole ocean,

00:22:04.150 --> 00:22:07.090
a trail of dark hair
running up my belly.

00:22:07.090 --> 00:22:11.140
My whole boat witness to
my small, naked frame,

00:22:11.140 --> 00:22:13.390
a gulf of shiver on the bus.

00:22:13.390 --> 00:22:17.140
And their own hairless legs
disappearing into their shorts,

00:22:17.140 --> 00:22:21.310
skin ripe as peaches,
reaching for my brown body.

00:22:21.310 --> 00:22:23.800
These girls who I
had stolen glances

00:22:23.800 --> 00:22:28.110
at while we changed and wished I
could look like, my locker room

00:22:28.110 --> 00:22:32.740
crew, my 5:00 AM practice girls,
my lean over the starboard side

00:22:32.740 --> 00:22:35.140
so she could pee off
the rigger girls,

00:22:35.140 --> 00:22:39.250
my two-mile run after eating
Annie's mac and cheese girls.

00:22:39.250 --> 00:22:41.200
They took turns
rubbing life back

00:22:41.200 --> 00:22:44.410
and my bones, offered
clothes off their own backs

00:22:44.410 --> 00:22:46.360
to keep me from shaking.

00:22:46.360 --> 00:22:50.650
My girls, sandwiching me in
their heat until my joints

00:22:50.650 --> 00:22:54.580
flowered, until the warmth
blooded through my blood.

00:22:54.580 --> 00:22:57.040
What more could
I ask than a team

00:22:57.040 --> 00:22:59.530
willing to undress
their captain, too

00:22:59.530 --> 00:23:03.100
cold and rain-glittered
to do it alone."

00:23:03.100 --> 00:23:04.922
Thank you.

00:23:04.922 --> 00:23:07.342
