00:23:17.022 --> 00:23:19.230
- Hi, everybody.

00:23:19.230 --> 00:23:20.770
Thank you so much for having me.

00:23:20.770 --> 00:23:25.220
I'm totally thrilled to be here
and feel completely humbled

00:23:25.220 --> 00:23:27.560
and a little bit
intimidated to be here

00:23:27.560 --> 00:23:31.880
with my amazing co-panelists.

00:23:31.880 --> 00:23:32.550
I'm Dana.

00:23:32.550 --> 00:23:34.760
I am a third-year in law school.

00:23:34.760 --> 00:23:38.210
Before I went to law
school, I organized students

00:23:38.210 --> 00:23:41.420
across the country to combat
sexual and gender violence

00:23:41.420 --> 00:23:43.190
in our schools.

00:23:43.190 --> 00:23:44.300
We passed good laws.

00:23:44.300 --> 00:23:46.160
We defeated bad laws.

00:23:46.160 --> 00:23:50.660
We organized for better policies
and practices in our schools.

00:23:50.660 --> 00:23:53.720
And then we turned around and
trained the slightly younger

00:23:53.720 --> 00:23:57.500
generation of [? next ?]
students to do the same.

00:23:57.500 --> 00:24:00.950
And the idea wasn't just
to mobilize young people

00:24:00.950 --> 00:24:03.860
on this one issue
of sexual violence

00:24:03.860 --> 00:24:07.430
but frankly to politicize
them and to develop

00:24:07.430 --> 00:24:09.800
their feminist
consciousness and endow them

00:24:09.800 --> 00:24:12.620
with the tools and the
skills that they were going

00:24:12.620 --> 00:24:16.730
to need to fight on any range of
progressive causes in the years

00:24:16.730 --> 00:24:19.400
ahead.

00:24:19.400 --> 00:24:22.940
Many of us in the contemporary
movement against gender

00:24:22.940 --> 00:24:27.020
violence met online after
we formed secret Facebook

00:24:27.020 --> 00:24:31.700
groups, groups with hundreds and
hundreds of survivors in them.

00:24:31.700 --> 00:24:35.420
We shared tips there
about managing flashbacks

00:24:35.420 --> 00:24:38.510
and crowdsourced
advice on dealing

00:24:38.510 --> 00:24:43.370
with a hostile,
unresponsive legal system.

00:24:43.370 --> 00:24:45.840
And in those Facebook
groups, we got angry.

00:24:45.840 --> 00:24:48.500
We circulated older
feminist writings.

00:24:48.500 --> 00:24:50.450
We planned protests.

00:24:50.450 --> 00:24:52.370
It was a form of
consciousness-raising,

00:24:52.370 --> 00:24:54.860
just online.

00:24:54.860 --> 00:24:58.280
And dissatisfied with
the lack of resources

00:24:58.280 --> 00:25:01.710
that were available to
us, we built our own.

00:25:01.710 --> 00:25:04.460
So with no legal
background or degrees,

00:25:04.460 --> 00:25:07.590
we built a website to share
with other students what

00:25:07.590 --> 00:25:12.410
we had learned the hard
way about our own rights.

00:25:12.410 --> 00:25:18.230
So this is all to say that my
small community and generation

00:25:18.230 --> 00:25:21.050
of feminists have relied
in really large part

00:25:21.050 --> 00:25:24.290
on the strategies and the tools
sharpened by the feminists who

00:25:24.290 --> 00:25:27.410
came in the 50 years before us.

00:25:27.410 --> 00:25:30.200
And it seems impossible
to me to talk

00:25:30.200 --> 00:25:32.180
about the contemporary
movement against gender

00:25:32.180 --> 00:25:36.410
violence in our schools without
talking about the second wave.

00:25:36.410 --> 00:25:38.660
Title IX, the landmark
civil rights law

00:25:38.660 --> 00:25:41.690
that, among other
things, requires schools

00:25:41.690 --> 00:25:44.270
to respond to sexual
harassment and violence,

00:25:44.270 --> 00:25:48.290
is itself, of course, a
product of the second wave.

00:25:48.290 --> 00:25:50.180
And the core insight
of the second wave,

00:25:50.180 --> 00:25:53.300
that the personal is political
and that private violence ought

00:25:53.300 --> 00:25:55.310
to be a matter of
public concern,

00:25:55.310 --> 00:25:59.000
lives on in our work today.

00:25:59.000 --> 00:26:02.030
But the central question,
as many of us see it today,

00:26:02.030 --> 00:26:04.490
is who should be
responsible for responding

00:26:04.490 --> 00:26:07.310
to the harms of violence.

00:26:07.310 --> 00:26:10.220
The white, mainstream
strand of the second wave,

00:26:10.220 --> 00:26:13.550
which demanded that the state
take gender violence seriously

00:26:13.550 --> 00:26:15.860
in the same way it took
other forms of violence

00:26:15.860 --> 00:26:19.130
seriously through the
police and prisons

00:26:19.130 --> 00:26:21.980
resulted in reforms ranging
from the criminalization

00:26:21.980 --> 00:26:27.110
of marital rape to dual and
mandatory arrest policies.

00:26:27.110 --> 00:26:30.660
And it coincided with the
rise of mass incarceration

00:26:30.660 --> 00:26:32.630
and with the idea
that incarceration

00:26:32.630 --> 00:26:36.110
should be the dominant
and the appropriate way

00:26:36.110 --> 00:26:39.830
to address all sorts of problems
in our country, problems that

00:26:39.830 --> 00:26:42.140
might otherwise have been
differently addressed

00:26:42.140 --> 00:26:44.870
through, say, a
focus on education

00:26:44.870 --> 00:26:48.390
or poverty or public health.

00:26:48.390 --> 00:26:51.340
As my friend Alexandra
Brodsky puts it,

00:26:51.340 --> 00:26:53.750
prisons really
came to monopolize

00:26:53.750 --> 00:26:59.440
our imaginations of the
right way to respond to harm.

00:26:59.440 --> 00:27:03.730
That's a legacy that many
of my peers want to undo.

00:27:03.730 --> 00:27:07.030
For us, part of the
appeal of Title IX

00:27:07.030 --> 00:27:09.460
has been its potential
to be an alternative

00:27:09.460 --> 00:27:13.360
to the moral failure of the
criminal legal system, a system

00:27:13.360 --> 00:27:17.320
that puts black and brown
men in cages, that threatens

00:27:17.320 --> 00:27:21.400
undocumented victims with
deportation, that criminalizes

00:27:21.400 --> 00:27:25.960
women of color when they fight
back against their abusers,

00:27:25.960 --> 00:27:29.170
and that does nothing meaningful
to end sexual violence,

00:27:29.170 --> 00:27:32.410
but actually fosters violence
against the people it's

00:27:32.410 --> 00:27:35.470
supposed to house and reform.

00:27:35.470 --> 00:27:38.560
So many young feminists are
asking the question if not

00:27:38.560 --> 00:27:39.835
this system, then what?

00:27:39.835 --> 00:27:41.140
What are the alternatives?

00:27:41.140 --> 00:27:43.150
And that's a question
that women of color

00:27:43.150 --> 00:27:45.920
have been asking for a
really, really long time

00:27:45.920 --> 00:27:47.380
and that groups
like Insight have

00:27:47.380 --> 00:27:50.770
been pioneering really
creative responses

00:27:50.770 --> 00:27:53.480
to for a really long time.

00:27:53.480 --> 00:27:56.680
But one alternative,
it seemed to my peers,

00:27:56.680 --> 00:27:59.500
was to marshal civil
rights law, Title IX,

00:27:59.500 --> 00:28:01.900
to require our
institutions to respond

00:28:01.900 --> 00:28:03.910
to the harms we're facing.

00:28:03.910 --> 00:28:07.160
Title IX prohibits sex
discrimination in education,

00:28:07.160 --> 00:28:09.010
not just in colleges
and universities

00:28:09.010 --> 00:28:12.430
as we hear about a lot, but
also in elementary schools

00:28:12.430 --> 00:28:14.750
and middle schools
and high schools.

00:28:14.750 --> 00:28:18.490
And because rape and harassment
can make it really hard to get

00:28:18.490 --> 00:28:21.970
an education, US courts
have long required schools

00:28:21.970 --> 00:28:24.670
to mitigate the harms of
this violence on student

00:28:24.670 --> 00:28:29.050
victims' lives and to really
focus on victims' needs

00:28:29.050 --> 00:28:32.530
in a way that the criminal
legal system doesn't and really

00:28:32.530 --> 00:28:34.070
can't.

00:28:34.070 --> 00:28:39.610
So I'm talking about how schools
must help victims relocate out

00:28:39.610 --> 00:28:42.190
of a dorm that they
shared with their abuser

00:28:42.190 --> 00:28:48.010
or off campus, free access to
a whole host of accommodations

00:28:48.010 --> 00:28:51.730
like therapy and
academic tutoring

00:28:51.730 --> 00:28:57.620
to help someone get back on
track in school after trauma.

00:28:57.620 --> 00:28:59.810
And of course, the
system isn't perfect.

00:28:59.810 --> 00:29:02.140
And certainly,
schools have all kinds

00:29:02.140 --> 00:29:06.190
of incentives as corporations
with bottom lines

00:29:06.190 --> 00:29:08.860
and reputations
at stake to get it

00:29:08.860 --> 00:29:15.046
wrong to the detriment of both
victims and accused students.

00:29:15.046 --> 00:29:18.400
Though you wouldn't know it from
how the media covers the issue,

00:29:18.400 --> 00:29:20.710
young feminists have been
thoughtfully thinking

00:29:20.710 --> 00:29:25.770
through what just discipline
should look like, too,

00:29:25.770 --> 00:29:28.480
and what protections a
just disciplinary process

00:29:28.480 --> 00:29:30.490
ought to have for
both students--

00:29:30.490 --> 00:29:31.870
victims and accused.

00:29:31.870 --> 00:29:34.690
So things like ensuring that
both parties have access

00:29:34.690 --> 00:29:36.340
to all the evidence
and adequate time

00:29:36.340 --> 00:29:38.650
to prepare their case,
that both parties are

00:29:38.650 --> 00:29:40.090
able to have a
neutral third party

00:29:40.090 --> 00:29:42.880
pose them questions
and examine them,

00:29:42.880 --> 00:29:46.030
that both parties have the right
to appeal the decisions that

00:29:46.030 --> 00:29:48.480
are handed down.

00:29:48.480 --> 00:29:50.980
And it's not just in schools
that we're thinking about this,

00:29:50.980 --> 00:29:52.930
but young feminist
groups like Know Your IX

00:29:52.930 --> 00:29:55.870
have been really
active in opposing

00:29:55.870 --> 00:29:59.320
the expansion of the
criminal legal system in sort

00:29:59.320 --> 00:30:03.290
of a unique way that, as
survivors, we're able to.

00:30:03.290 --> 00:30:07.180
So a couple years ago, we
defeated this Delaware bill,

00:30:07.180 --> 00:30:11.320
which was backed by second-wave
Democrat lawmakers that

00:30:11.320 --> 00:30:15.570
would force schools to hand
rape reports over to the police

00:30:15.570 --> 00:30:18.700
with or without
survivors' consent.

00:30:18.700 --> 00:30:21.310
And those bills, which have
really proliferated in states

00:30:21.310 --> 00:30:23.230
all across the
country, don't just

00:30:23.230 --> 00:30:25.690
undermine survivor autonomy.

00:30:25.690 --> 00:30:27.820
They also limit the
range of options

00:30:27.820 --> 00:30:30.640
that survivors
can pursue, making

00:30:30.640 --> 00:30:34.570
victims who have reason to fear
the police afraid to report

00:30:34.570 --> 00:30:37.870
to anyone, including
their school.

00:30:37.870 --> 00:30:41.470
Likewise-- and I'll wrap up in
a minute-- but this last year,

00:30:41.470 --> 00:30:44.211
Know Your IX and other groups
opposed the recalled Judge

00:30:44.211 --> 00:30:44.710
Persky.

00:30:44.710 --> 00:30:47.110
He was the judge who
gave Brock Turner

00:30:47.110 --> 00:30:51.400
that infamous six-month sentence
for raping an unconscious woman

00:30:51.400 --> 00:30:52.990
at Stanford.

00:30:52.990 --> 00:30:55.420
And certainly, the sentence
that Persky imposed

00:30:55.420 --> 00:30:57.940
was sexist and
racist and classist

00:30:57.940 --> 00:31:02.650
and was rooted in the idea that
white boys who swim at Stanford

00:31:02.650 --> 00:31:05.560
deserve endless second chances.

00:31:05.560 --> 00:31:08.680
But the response of recalling
the judge we feared would cause

00:31:08.680 --> 00:31:11.920
other judges to issue ever
more punitive rulings,

00:31:11.920 --> 00:31:15.560
afraid of losing their
jobs if they didn't.

00:31:15.560 --> 00:31:17.680
Anyway, the point
of our critique

00:31:17.680 --> 00:31:22.480
here isn't to shame survivors
who choose to go to the police.

00:31:22.480 --> 00:31:25.480
In a world with really
severely limited options,

00:31:25.480 --> 00:31:27.690
it's understandable
to seek recourse

00:31:27.690 --> 00:31:30.435
wherever you can find it.

00:31:30.435 --> 00:31:32.560
And the point also isn't
to insist that Title IX is

00:31:32.560 --> 00:31:34.030
a perfect alternative here.

00:31:34.030 --> 00:31:35.920
I don't think it is.

00:31:35.920 --> 00:31:38.710
Rather, it's to say this,
which is that we shouldn't have

00:31:38.710 --> 00:31:40.650
to be afraid in our schools.

00:31:40.650 --> 00:31:44.410
And we shouldn't have to choose
between enduring harassment

00:31:44.410 --> 00:31:48.650
in our workplaces and not
bringing home a paycheck.

00:31:48.650 --> 00:31:51.280
We need alternatives
beyond the criminal system

00:31:51.280 --> 00:31:55.270
to make right the harm that
violence creates in our lives.

00:31:55.270 --> 00:31:57.100
And we need systems
that discourage

00:31:57.100 --> 00:31:59.550
that harm in the first place.

00:31:59.550 --> 00:32:02.490
I think this is one of the
central questions my generation

00:32:02.490 --> 00:32:03.870
is going to need to figure out.

00:32:03.870 --> 00:32:08.160
And I feel really
glad that there

00:32:08.160 --> 00:32:12.030
are so many smart,
creative young feminists

00:32:12.030 --> 00:32:14.676
in that fight with us.

00:32:14.676 --> 00:32:15.672
Thank you.

00:32:15.672 --> 00:32:18.162
[APPLAUSE]

