00:33:09.530 --> 00:33:11.360
feels sort of sweet
in a personal way,

00:33:11.360 --> 00:33:12.830
because when I was--

00:33:12.830 --> 00:33:15.647
about 20 years
ago when I was 16,

00:33:15.647 --> 00:33:17.480
I dropped out of high
school and got my GED,

00:33:17.480 --> 00:33:20.030
and I moved to Boston
and I took night classes

00:33:20.030 --> 00:33:21.050
at Harvard Extension.

00:33:21.050 --> 00:33:23.900
And I took mostly feminist
history classes and also

00:33:23.900 --> 00:33:24.830
some creative writing.

00:33:24.830 --> 00:33:27.920
And so it just feels
sweet, like I sort of

00:33:27.920 --> 00:33:31.100
wish I could go back to
that very brave and arrogant

00:33:31.100 --> 00:33:34.220
young person and let her know
that it was going to work out

00:33:34.220 --> 00:33:35.320
and I would be here today.

00:33:35.320 --> 00:33:39.410
So thank you for
allowing me that.

00:33:39.410 --> 00:33:41.430
And you heard, I'm also
on the board of VIDA.

00:33:41.430 --> 00:33:45.440
And with my colleague,
Hafizah, over here,

00:33:45.440 --> 00:33:47.090
helped co-curate this event.

00:33:47.090 --> 00:33:49.070
And you heard a
little bit about VIDA

00:33:49.070 --> 00:33:50.932
from Jane in the introduction.

00:33:50.932 --> 00:33:52.640
And I'll expand on
that a little bit more

00:33:52.640 --> 00:33:55.130
to illustrate some
of the ways that I

00:33:55.130 --> 00:34:00.080
think we are an example of a
certain kind of feminism now.

00:34:00.080 --> 00:34:04.130
So for those of you who don't
know, almost 10 years ago now,

00:34:04.130 --> 00:34:07.305
the VIDA founders,
who are all poets,

00:34:07.305 --> 00:34:09.679
were having a conversation
with each other about the lack

00:34:09.679 --> 00:34:11.870
of gender parity that
they saw in the magazines

00:34:11.870 --> 00:34:13.520
where they wanted
to see their work

00:34:13.520 --> 00:34:15.311
and in the review
outlets where they wanted

00:34:15.311 --> 00:34:16.812
to see their work reviewed.

00:34:16.812 --> 00:34:18.770
And it was a conversation
that they, of course,

00:34:18.770 --> 00:34:22.880
had had before, that women
have always been having.

00:34:22.880 --> 00:34:25.280
But they decided to concretize
what they were seeing.

00:34:25.280 --> 00:34:27.175
And they wanted to make
other people see it.

00:34:27.175 --> 00:34:28.550
Because they were
tired of making

00:34:28.550 --> 00:34:30.020
that really obvious argument.

00:34:30.020 --> 00:34:32.570
So they undertook this
massive data collection

00:34:32.570 --> 00:34:34.250
and collected
hundreds of the years

00:34:34.250 --> 00:34:38.360
tables of contents and
physically counted the women

00:34:38.360 --> 00:34:40.580
that they could recognize.

00:34:40.580 --> 00:34:45.770
And they counted reviewers,
authors of books reviewed,

00:34:45.770 --> 00:34:48.679
and bylines in top-tier
magazines like The New Yorker

00:34:48.679 --> 00:34:50.120
and so forth.

00:34:50.120 --> 00:34:53.330
And the pie charts that resulted
proved what they already

00:34:53.330 --> 00:34:57.050
knew, that women were profoundly
under-represented in all

00:34:57.050 --> 00:34:58.370
of those spaces.

00:34:58.370 --> 00:35:01.100
And in the 10 years since
then, the annual VIDA Count

00:35:01.100 --> 00:35:03.530
has become something of a
household name, at least

00:35:03.530 --> 00:35:05.450
among writers.

00:35:05.450 --> 00:35:08.360
And many of those early and
worst offenders, the somewhat

00:35:08.360 --> 00:35:10.670
repentant ones or at
least publicly repentant

00:35:10.670 --> 00:35:13.250
ones, as Jane pointed
out, have admitted

00:35:13.250 --> 00:35:17.420
to consciously working to
improve their VIDA numbers.

00:35:17.420 --> 00:35:18.980
And since then,
in these 10 years,

00:35:18.980 --> 00:35:22.250
VIDA has also grown in
some other directions.

00:35:22.250 --> 00:35:26.000
Kimberle Crenshaw, who coined
the term "intersectionality"

00:35:26.000 --> 00:35:28.760
and the analytic framework
said recently in an interview

00:35:28.760 --> 00:35:31.280
that "intersectionality is
the lens through which you

00:35:31.280 --> 00:35:33.800
can see where power
comes and collides,

00:35:33.800 --> 00:35:36.140
where it interlocks
and intersects.

00:35:36.140 --> 00:35:38.660
It's not simply that there's
a race problem here, a gender

00:35:38.660 --> 00:35:42.650
problem here, a class
or LGBTQ problem here.

00:35:42.650 --> 00:35:44.480
Many times that
framework erases what

00:35:44.480 --> 00:35:46.400
happens to people who
are subject to all

00:35:46.400 --> 00:35:48.680
of these things."

00:35:48.680 --> 00:35:53.040
And Fatimah also
talked about this some.

00:35:53.040 --> 00:35:55.400
I've worked primarily with
sort of the second generation

00:35:55.400 --> 00:35:58.940
of VIDA leadership, along with
my two colleagues who are here

00:35:58.940 --> 00:36:01.800
today, Hafizah Geter
and Camille Rankine, who

00:36:01.800 --> 00:36:03.680
is our present executive
committee chair.

00:36:03.680 --> 00:36:05.630
Can you guys just wave?

00:36:05.630 --> 00:36:08.210
These women have done so
much work for this event

00:36:08.210 --> 00:36:08.840
and in general.

00:36:08.840 --> 00:36:11.030
[APPLAUSE]

00:36:11.030 --> 00:36:12.560
And in recent
years, VIDA's focus

00:36:12.560 --> 00:36:15.350
has broadened in this
consciously intersectional

00:36:15.350 --> 00:36:17.480
direction, because we
don't just have a gender

00:36:17.480 --> 00:36:20.020
problem in the literary world.

00:36:20.020 --> 00:36:24.360
And the count is now plural
and examines race, disability,

00:36:24.360 --> 00:36:25.780
sexual identity, and age.

00:36:25.780 --> 00:36:27.560
And it's ever expanding.

00:36:27.560 --> 00:36:29.000
And we're refining
our techniques

00:36:29.000 --> 00:36:32.150
for counting those categories.

00:36:32.150 --> 00:36:35.390
So the priority of VIDA
today is a bit broader

00:36:35.390 --> 00:36:36.710
than it was in the beginning.

00:36:36.710 --> 00:36:38.690
It's to examine and
raise consciousness

00:36:38.690 --> 00:36:42.320
about these interlocking and
intersecting systems of power

00:36:42.320 --> 00:36:45.830
in the literary world, which
is, of course, a microcosm

00:36:45.830 --> 00:36:48.530
of our greater world,
and to create spaces

00:36:48.530 --> 00:36:51.800
on stages like this,
in our online magazine,

00:36:51.800 --> 00:36:53.690
and through programs
like saferLIT

00:36:53.690 --> 00:36:56.240
where those most disempowered
intersectional voices can

00:36:56.240 --> 00:36:58.920
be heard and protected.

00:36:58.920 --> 00:37:01.310
So I'm here on this panel
as a VIDA board member

00:37:01.310 --> 00:37:03.500
but also as a feminist artist.

00:37:03.500 --> 00:37:06.110
So I want to talk a little
bit about my own path

00:37:06.110 --> 00:37:09.410
and the relationship between my
art and my activism and the way

00:37:09.410 --> 00:37:14.170
that our work at VIDA is sort
of at the nexus of those things.

00:37:14.170 --> 00:37:16.470
So I'm on the cusp of
what some recognize

00:37:16.470 --> 00:37:17.850
as the millennial cutoff.

00:37:20.790 --> 00:37:24.120
And I was raised by a very
serious second-wave feminist,

00:37:24.120 --> 00:37:27.070
by which I mean that as a
tiny person in a stroller,

00:37:27.070 --> 00:37:31.590
I spent a lot of time
lounging at marches.

00:37:31.590 --> 00:37:34.170
And when I learned
to read, I discovered

00:37:34.170 --> 00:37:37.440
that my mother had corrected
all of my fairy tale books

00:37:37.440 --> 00:37:40.470
with a Sharpie to
change the pronouns so

00:37:40.470 --> 00:37:46.620
that the female characters
got most of the heroism.

00:37:46.620 --> 00:37:49.620
It was Gretel who came up with
the idea with the bread crumbs

00:37:49.620 --> 00:37:52.250
in my book.

00:37:52.250 --> 00:37:55.450
And my bedtime lullabies
were Holly Near songs.

00:37:55.450 --> 00:37:57.100
Anybody here-- yes.

00:37:57.100 --> 00:37:57.600
OK.

00:37:57.600 --> 00:38:00.050
"Power" was my favorite.

00:38:00.050 --> 00:38:02.790
And my first concert was Sweet
Honey in the Rock, probably

00:38:02.790 --> 00:38:04.440
still the best.

00:38:04.440 --> 00:38:06.180
The first literary
accolade that I ever

00:38:06.180 --> 00:38:08.790
won was a poetry prize
for girls from NOW,

00:38:08.790 --> 00:38:10.440
the National
Organization for Women,

00:38:10.440 --> 00:38:13.740
which as Jane pointed out,
houses their archives here

00:38:13.740 --> 00:38:14.460
at the library.

00:38:14.460 --> 00:38:15.690
- We have Holly Near, too.

00:38:15.690 --> 00:38:17.330
- You have Holly Near also?

00:38:17.330 --> 00:38:19.452
We'll talk.

00:38:19.452 --> 00:38:20.910
The meetings of
whose local chapter

00:38:20.910 --> 00:38:23.010
I regularly attended with
my mom and her friends

00:38:23.010 --> 00:38:27.670
and played with my
LEGOs in the back.

00:38:27.670 --> 00:38:30.300
I was also obsessed
with Ms Magazine.

00:38:30.300 --> 00:38:32.457
And I borrowed the name
of its back page column.

00:38:32.457 --> 00:38:34.290
I don't think they've
done this for a while,

00:38:34.290 --> 00:38:36.660
but does anybody
remember "No Comment."

00:38:36.660 --> 00:38:39.110
It was like readers would
send in misogynistic ads,

00:38:39.110 --> 00:38:40.980
and they would collage
them on the back.

00:38:40.980 --> 00:38:43.580
They never published
the ads that I sent in.

00:38:43.580 --> 00:38:46.320
But I loved it so much,
that I named my zine

00:38:46.320 --> 00:38:49.530
when I was 14 after
the back page of Ms.

00:38:49.530 --> 00:38:52.560
And it was also
called "No Comment."

00:38:52.560 --> 00:38:55.770
And I photocopied the issues of
my zine at our local library,

00:38:55.770 --> 00:38:58.500
and then I distributed them
at my small-town high school

00:38:58.500 --> 00:38:59.970
in Cape Cod.

00:38:59.970 --> 00:39:05.010
I was very popular, as you can
imagine, as the only girl who

00:39:05.010 --> 00:39:08.260
shaved her head but not her
legs in my whole school, who

00:39:08.260 --> 00:39:10.920
was an out bisexual, who
knew all the words to Bikini

00:39:10.920 --> 00:39:13.860
Kill and Ani DiFranco.

00:39:13.860 --> 00:39:15.660
I literally can't
remember a time

00:39:15.660 --> 00:39:17.370
when I didn't
identify as a feminist

00:39:17.370 --> 00:39:20.060
or I didn't know that I
wanted to be a writer.

00:39:20.060 --> 00:39:22.320
And I became conscious
of my own privilege

00:39:22.320 --> 00:39:26.460
and my own intersecting
identity around the same time

00:39:26.460 --> 00:39:28.890
that Crenshaw coined the term,
although it was another 20

00:39:28.890 --> 00:39:30.790
years or so before I heard it.

00:39:30.790 --> 00:39:32.412
Though I've always
identified as white

00:39:32.412 --> 00:39:34.620
and experience the privileges
of being read that way,

00:39:34.620 --> 00:39:36.420
I come from an
interracial family,

00:39:36.420 --> 00:39:39.300
which felt really simple in
some ways inside of our home

00:39:39.300 --> 00:39:42.740
and more complicated in other
ways outside of our home.

00:39:42.740 --> 00:39:45.300
And it wasn't until college,
until I came here, actually,

00:39:45.300 --> 00:39:47.640
that my understanding
of feminism

00:39:47.640 --> 00:39:49.740
included a larger
dialogue about race.

00:39:49.740 --> 00:39:52.680
And even then, it didn't really
dig into those more nuanced

00:39:52.680 --> 00:39:53.680
intricacies.

00:39:53.680 --> 00:39:56.730
I'm also the queer
daughter of a queer mother.

00:39:56.730 --> 00:39:58.410
But as femme-presenting
women, we

00:39:58.410 --> 00:40:01.470
have often been invisible
and assumed straight.

00:40:01.470 --> 00:40:03.542
And in my early 20s,
I became a sex worker.

00:40:03.542 --> 00:40:05.250
And the discourse
around that experience,

00:40:05.250 --> 00:40:09.360
even among feminists, maybe
especially among feminists,

00:40:09.360 --> 00:40:13.240
didn't seem to leave room
from my own experience.

00:40:13.240 --> 00:40:16.740
So all of these aspects, and
not only these aspects of me,

00:40:16.740 --> 00:40:20.274
felt fraught, laden with
both privilege and erasure.

00:40:20.274 --> 00:40:21.690
And the feminism
I'd grown up with

00:40:21.690 --> 00:40:24.750
didn't give me a map for
how to parse that out,

00:40:24.750 --> 00:40:28.010
how I could be both marginalized
and privileged at the same time

00:40:28.010 --> 00:40:30.540
or how to reconcile all of
those hybrid identities.

00:40:30.540 --> 00:40:33.540
I felt so many
things that I just

00:40:33.540 --> 00:40:37.380
felt like I could claim
nothing, a lot of the time.

00:40:37.380 --> 00:40:41.360
So writing became a place really
early on for me, really young,

00:40:41.360 --> 00:40:43.980
where I tried to put words
to the aspects of myself

00:40:43.980 --> 00:40:47.940
and my world that felt unnamed,
even within my own politics.

00:40:47.940 --> 00:40:49.980
And it has always been
that, a place where

00:40:49.980 --> 00:40:52.470
I try to speak what feels
unspoken, discouraged,

00:40:52.470 --> 00:40:54.900
incomprehensible, incompatible.

00:40:54.900 --> 00:40:58.140
And as a teacher, that's how I
present writing to my students.

00:40:58.140 --> 00:41:00.600
And that practice has
defined both the content

00:41:00.600 --> 00:41:02.220
and the form of my work.

00:41:02.220 --> 00:41:04.770
So I write mostly
nonfiction, but I

00:41:04.770 --> 00:41:07.890
borrow elements of poetry
and memoir and scholarship

00:41:07.890 --> 00:41:08.700
and criticism.

00:41:08.700 --> 00:41:11.931
And like me, it's a hybrid
thing most of the time.

00:41:11.931 --> 00:41:13.680
And when I finally did
find the literature

00:41:13.680 --> 00:41:16.800
of intersectionality, it
felt like this huge relief

00:41:16.800 --> 00:41:18.390
to see it named.

00:41:18.390 --> 00:41:20.990
And that more holistic view
of our culture's sickness,

00:41:20.990 --> 00:41:22.830
its fundamental
power imbalances,

00:41:22.830 --> 00:41:26.310
seems, to me at least, also
to reflect the interconnected

00:41:26.310 --> 00:41:29.520
nature of my own identity
and my work and my activism

00:41:29.520 --> 00:41:30.690
and my art.

00:41:30.690 --> 00:41:32.640
None of it is separate for me.

00:41:32.640 --> 00:41:35.880
And so working with VIDA
seems like the perfect example

00:41:35.880 --> 00:41:36.980
of that integration.

00:41:36.980 --> 00:41:40.500
All of us at VIDA are feminists,
writers, teachers, editors,

00:41:40.500 --> 00:41:42.870
folks who often claim the
intersectional identities

00:41:42.870 --> 00:41:43.974
that we champion.

00:41:43.974 --> 00:41:46.140
And we're all interested
in leveraging our privilege

00:41:46.140 --> 00:41:47.910
to further that cause.

00:41:47.910 --> 00:41:49.440
We each bring to
the organization

00:41:49.440 --> 00:41:52.590
our own particular strengths
and employ them in our activism.

00:41:52.590 --> 00:41:54.900
And it's part of our
art and our social lives

00:41:54.900 --> 00:41:55.779
and our professions.

00:41:55.779 --> 00:41:57.570
And I think it's
impossible for a lot of us

00:41:57.570 --> 00:41:58.759
to distinguish those things.

00:41:58.759 --> 00:42:00.300
And in that way, I
think we're really

00:42:00.300 --> 00:42:04.320
typical of a certain kind
of contemporary feminism.

00:42:04.320 --> 00:42:07.410
And I can see the ways that
my mother's feminism grew out

00:42:07.410 --> 00:42:10.730
of that of the suffragists, how
it complicated and corrected

00:42:10.730 --> 00:42:12.740
and advanced much of that work.

00:42:12.740 --> 00:42:15.710
And I can also see the way the
third-wave feminists grew out

00:42:15.710 --> 00:42:17.990
of and reinvented the
consciousness-raising groups

00:42:17.990 --> 00:42:20.060
of the '60s and '70s.

00:42:20.060 --> 00:42:21.710
And I can see the
ways that my feminism

00:42:21.710 --> 00:42:23.810
and its intersectional
focus is a correction

00:42:23.810 --> 00:42:25.370
to the history of
white feminism,

00:42:25.370 --> 00:42:28.130
to Betty Friedan's fear
of the lavender menace,

00:42:28.130 --> 00:42:30.800
as I can also find its early
echoes in the Bill of Rights

00:42:30.800 --> 00:42:33.500
for NOW, which was
adopted in 1967

00:42:33.500 --> 00:42:35.180
and speaks explicitly
about the need

00:42:35.180 --> 00:42:37.640
for economic and racial justice.

00:42:37.640 --> 00:42:40.800
So-- I'm almost done--

00:42:40.800 --> 00:42:45.290
feminisms now, I think, are the
result of centuries of mindful

00:42:45.290 --> 00:42:47.330
feminist work, the
work of activists

00:42:47.330 --> 00:42:48.830
who recognize that
if we are going

00:42:48.830 --> 00:42:53.360
to sustain our work, our
waves, but not troughs,

00:42:53.360 --> 00:42:56.780
we needed a more expansive
space for feminism.

00:42:56.780 --> 00:42:59.090
We needed a feminism
capacious enough for us

00:42:59.090 --> 00:43:02.030
to work together and also
alongside one another.

00:43:02.030 --> 00:43:03.770
We needed multiple feminisms.

00:43:03.770 --> 00:43:05.510
And I do think
that we have them.

00:43:05.510 --> 00:43:09.020
I think that you're looking
at them, in many ways.

00:43:09.020 --> 00:43:11.450
And I'll end with a quote
from one of my heroes, one

00:43:11.450 --> 00:43:13.310
that I was reminded
of recently in a talk

00:43:13.310 --> 00:43:16.670
by the wonderful feminist
novelist Randa Jarrar.

00:43:16.670 --> 00:43:19.970
So at the 1981 conference of
the American Writers Congress,

00:43:19.970 --> 00:43:22.370
which sounds fancy, but
it was really small,

00:43:22.370 --> 00:43:25.670
Toni Morrison, who was an
editor then at Random House,

00:43:25.670 --> 00:43:28.460
told the audience, "We
don't need any more

00:43:28.460 --> 00:43:30.650
writers as solitary heroes.

00:43:30.650 --> 00:43:33.080
We need a heroic
writers' movement,

00:43:33.080 --> 00:43:36.110
assertive, militant,
pugnacious."

00:43:36.110 --> 00:43:39.650
And those words-- writing
them gave me a chill.

00:43:39.650 --> 00:43:44.840
Reading them-- they make my
armpit hair stand up on end.

00:43:44.840 --> 00:43:47.780
Because I think we actually
have right now not one

00:43:47.780 --> 00:43:51.740
heroic feminist movement,
not solitary feminist heroes,

00:43:51.740 --> 00:43:55.280
but a wide-ranging set of
heroic feminist movements.

00:43:55.280 --> 00:43:58.330
Because the feminists I work
with today, these people,

00:43:58.330 --> 00:44:00.890
they are as flexible and
creative and connected

00:44:00.890 --> 00:44:03.380
as they are assertive,
militant, and pugnacious.

00:44:03.380 --> 00:44:05.870
So I want to thank them
and thank you and thank

00:44:05.870 --> 00:44:06.830
my fellow panelists.

00:44:06.830 --> 00:44:09.275
[APPLAUSE]

