00:45:32.710 --> 00:45:35.740
So after I got that
out of the way--

00:45:35.740 --> 00:45:41.749
so I started For Harriet
in 2010 when I was 20.

00:45:41.749 --> 00:45:42.790
That was eight years ago.

00:45:42.790 --> 00:45:43.190
How old am I?

00:45:43.190 --> 00:45:43.731
I don't know.

00:45:43.731 --> 00:45:50.180
So anyways, it was the spring
of my junior year in college.

00:45:50.180 --> 00:45:51.930
I'm not going to get
into the whole story.

00:45:51.930 --> 00:45:58.080
But basically, I
was politely asked

00:45:58.080 --> 00:46:03.690
by Harvard College after junior
year not to return in the fall.

00:46:03.690 --> 00:46:05.310
And so I was kicked
out of school.

00:46:05.310 --> 00:46:06.060
I failed out.

00:46:06.060 --> 00:46:07.680
But I came back and graduated.

00:46:07.680 --> 00:46:08.680
It's a whole long story.

00:46:08.680 --> 00:46:11.110
We can, you know--

00:46:11.110 --> 00:46:15.630
But that summer, I
launched For Harriet.

00:46:15.630 --> 00:46:17.250
And it was a digital community.

00:46:17.250 --> 00:46:19.800
It is a digital community
for black women.

00:46:19.800 --> 00:46:23.260
And at that point, my
desire was to create

00:46:23.260 --> 00:46:25.530
intergenerational conversations.

00:46:25.530 --> 00:46:26.940
I was incredibly lost.

00:46:26.940 --> 00:46:28.410
I was stressed out.

00:46:28.410 --> 00:46:33.510
I recognized how
important and how

00:46:33.510 --> 00:46:36.600
fortifying the deep
connections that I

00:46:36.600 --> 00:46:40.020
had developed with black
women of different ages

00:46:40.020 --> 00:46:41.190
here had been for me.

00:46:41.190 --> 00:46:44.580
So I wanted to recreate
that space online.

00:46:44.580 --> 00:46:48.930
So originally, For Harriet
was about dialogue.

00:46:48.930 --> 00:46:51.480
At that point, I was
already a progressive.

00:46:51.480 --> 00:46:53.340
I was already a feminist.

00:46:53.340 --> 00:46:58.290
And so I knew that I wanted For
Harriet to be an intentionally

00:46:58.290 --> 00:47:01.680
progressive space, an
intentionally feminist space,

00:47:01.680 --> 00:47:04.980
where we encourage dialogue,
but the kind of dialogue that

00:47:04.980 --> 00:47:07.080
was going to move us forward.

00:47:07.080 --> 00:47:11.220
And from starting this
community in 2010,

00:47:11.220 --> 00:47:15.660
I was able to be really
plugged into black women's

00:47:15.660 --> 00:47:17.290
digital spaces.

00:47:17.290 --> 00:47:22.210
So this was way back when
everybody had Facebook,

00:47:22.210 --> 00:47:24.180
but not really.

00:47:24.180 --> 00:47:28.920
And it was the earlier
days of Twitter.

00:47:28.920 --> 00:47:30.930
And Tumblr was a big deal.

00:47:33.900 --> 00:47:39.530
So there were so many ways for
us to communicate and dialogue.

00:47:39.530 --> 00:47:44.426
And I wanted to be able to
be a leading voice there.

00:47:44.426 --> 00:47:45.800
I decided not to
script this out.

00:47:45.800 --> 00:47:49.140
I did a talk about a month
ago, and it was so scripted,

00:47:49.140 --> 00:47:51.840
and I realized the script
was a straight jacket for me.

00:47:51.840 --> 00:47:54.520
So we're going to
loosey goosey it here.

00:47:54.520 --> 00:47:57.990
All right.

00:47:57.990 --> 00:48:03.840
So I always want to
underscore that I

00:48:03.840 --> 00:48:06.630
am a very proud feminist.

00:48:06.630 --> 00:48:11.280
I am amazed by the way
that feminist ideas

00:48:11.280 --> 00:48:13.110
have been mainstreamed.

00:48:13.110 --> 00:48:15.900
But I always want to
underscore that we do not

00:48:15.900 --> 00:48:19.000
get to this place societially.

00:48:19.000 --> 00:48:21.390
We do not get to
the MeToo movement.

00:48:21.390 --> 00:48:24.360
We do not get to
intersectional feminism

00:48:24.360 --> 00:48:27.403
without the work and the
theory of black women.

00:48:27.403 --> 00:48:28.270
[APPLAUSE]

00:48:28.270 --> 00:48:28.820
Yeah.

00:48:28.820 --> 00:48:29.320
Yeah.

00:48:32.010 --> 00:48:34.410
It is so interesting
to me the way

00:48:34.410 --> 00:48:37.110
that intersectionality
has been mainstreamed.

00:48:37.110 --> 00:48:40.130
The other day, my mom, who
is not a feminist per se,

00:48:40.130 --> 00:48:42.660
said, oh, it's the
intersectionality.

00:48:42.660 --> 00:48:45.060
And I said, it's the what?

00:48:45.060 --> 00:48:48.570
But that is because
these ideas that

00:48:48.570 --> 00:48:51.720
used to be confined to
the, quote, unquote,

00:48:51.720 --> 00:48:54.300
"ivory tower," they
have worked their way

00:48:54.300 --> 00:48:57.810
into popular discourse.

00:48:57.810 --> 00:49:00.210
And that has only happened
because of the work

00:49:00.210 --> 00:49:03.270
that black women have
been doing online.

00:49:03.270 --> 00:49:05.460
Often when we talk about
the digital divide,

00:49:05.460 --> 00:49:08.610
we talk about how black
folks have less opportunity

00:49:08.610 --> 00:49:10.530
to access digital technologies.

00:49:10.530 --> 00:49:14.430
Sorry, my contract is about
to do something weird.

00:49:14.430 --> 00:49:16.710
We often talk about
the digital divide

00:49:16.710 --> 00:49:19.740
as coming from a
place of black, right?

00:49:19.740 --> 00:49:25.800
Black people don't have access
to the newest technologies.

00:49:25.800 --> 00:49:28.200
But I think that we see--

00:49:28.200 --> 00:49:30.240
and the way that
black women's work

00:49:30.240 --> 00:49:34.290
has infected mass movement--

00:49:34.290 --> 00:49:36.090
I mean, we don't get
to the Women's March

00:49:36.090 --> 00:49:38.520
without the work of black women.

00:49:38.520 --> 00:49:45.580
I think of that divide as a
source of enormous opportunity.

00:49:45.580 --> 00:49:49.110
Black women have
used these spaces--

00:49:49.110 --> 00:49:51.330
Twitter, Facebook,
Tumblr spaces--

00:49:51.330 --> 00:49:53.130
that were not made for us.

00:49:53.130 --> 00:49:56.190
And they were not
made with us in mind.

00:49:56.190 --> 00:49:59.730
But we have innovated
in these spaces

00:49:59.730 --> 00:50:05.730
and been able to shape
and craft this discourse

00:50:05.730 --> 00:50:09.360
in this back-and-forth and
doing this real-time theorizing

00:50:09.360 --> 00:50:12.570
and doing it in a
way that sticks.

00:50:12.570 --> 00:50:15.300
And that is really,
really incredible.

00:50:15.300 --> 00:50:19.200
And so for me at For
Harriet, as I've gotten older

00:50:19.200 --> 00:50:21.480
and grown in my
feminism, I wanted

00:50:21.480 --> 00:50:23.250
to not just have dialogue.

00:50:23.250 --> 00:50:25.620
But I wanted to cultivate
the sort of dialogue

00:50:25.620 --> 00:50:29.040
that moves us forward.

00:50:29.040 --> 00:50:31.500
Patricia Hill Collins says
in Black Feminist Thoughts--

00:50:31.500 --> 00:50:33.360
I do a lot of citation.

00:50:33.360 --> 00:50:36.537
I think a robust citational
practice is really important.

00:50:36.537 --> 00:50:38.370
It's a really important
part of my feminism.

00:50:38.370 --> 00:50:41.940
Patricia Hill Collins notes
in Black Feminist Thought

00:50:41.940 --> 00:50:45.900
that the way that we transform
societies is twofold.

00:50:45.900 --> 00:50:48.730
So it's doing that
internal work,

00:50:48.730 --> 00:50:52.650
changing how you understand
yourself and the world.

00:50:52.650 --> 00:50:54.510
And then you do
the external work,

00:50:54.510 --> 00:50:57.240
like changing power relations.

00:50:57.240 --> 00:51:01.950
And so I love doing the work
in black women's communities

00:51:01.950 --> 00:51:05.060
of working on that
internal stuff

00:51:05.060 --> 00:51:07.190
and making sure that
it goes outward.

00:51:07.190 --> 00:51:15.120
So like I said, whenever I make
videos or whenever I'm tweeting

00:51:15.120 --> 00:51:18.540
or whenever I'm editing
or writing articles,

00:51:18.540 --> 00:51:22.650
I make sure to cite
the black women

00:51:22.650 --> 00:51:24.990
theorists, the black
women activists who

00:51:24.990 --> 00:51:27.720
have set the stage for
what we are doing now.

00:51:27.720 --> 00:51:30.360
And it's really important for
me to do that because I often

00:51:30.360 --> 00:51:33.750
find black women have--

00:51:33.750 --> 00:51:37.470
they are not so apt,
often, to embrace

00:51:37.470 --> 00:51:40.450
the idea of being feminists.

00:51:40.450 --> 00:51:41.760
People say, I'm not a feminist.

00:51:41.760 --> 00:51:44.190
I'm a womanist and
all of this stuff.

00:51:44.190 --> 00:51:46.200
Because they imagine
feminism as being something

00:51:46.200 --> 00:51:47.550
that is for white women.

00:51:47.550 --> 00:51:51.090
One of the reasons why I have
a robust citational practice

00:51:51.090 --> 00:51:55.650
is to underscore the fact
that we don't just get here,

00:51:55.650 --> 00:51:59.220
that black women built this.

00:51:59.220 --> 00:52:01.080
This house of black
women and women

00:52:01.080 --> 00:52:04.840
of color, the house that we
are currently standing in

00:52:04.840 --> 00:52:08.550
is not just a house that we
just walked in in 2015, right?

00:52:08.550 --> 00:52:11.850
It is a house that we
constructed brick by brick.

00:52:11.850 --> 00:52:13.110
That is our labor.

00:52:13.110 --> 00:52:14.040
That is our work.

00:52:14.040 --> 00:52:15.000
That is our activism.

00:52:15.000 --> 00:52:16.180
That is our theory.

00:52:16.180 --> 00:52:19.770
And so I always want to
be able to communicate

00:52:19.770 --> 00:52:23.730
to black women of all
generations that this is us.

00:52:23.730 --> 00:52:25.900
This is ours.

00:52:25.900 --> 00:52:28.860
A long time ago, Barack Obama
said, you didn't build that.

00:52:28.860 --> 00:52:30.810
No, we did build this.

00:52:30.810 --> 00:52:33.530
We did build this.

00:52:33.530 --> 00:52:36.870
And so another part of the
work that I am doing now

00:52:36.870 --> 00:52:40.470
at Four Harriet and the work
that I'm doing personally

00:52:40.470 --> 00:52:42.630
as I'm working on
this book project

00:52:42.630 --> 00:52:48.180
is trying to outline what does
a feminist life look like?

00:52:48.180 --> 00:52:49.980
Not to steal from Sara Ahmed.

00:52:49.980 --> 00:52:54.450
She has an amazing book,
Living a Feminist Life.

00:52:54.450 --> 00:52:56.520
But really approaching
that question

00:52:56.520 --> 00:53:02.010
from the unique positionality
of a 29-year-old black woman,

00:53:02.010 --> 00:53:05.720
a millennial black woman, whose
feminism has been constructed

00:53:05.720 --> 00:53:08.750
by all of those women who
came before but has also

00:53:08.750 --> 00:53:12.350
been constructed and mediated
by digital technologies

00:53:12.350 --> 00:53:15.470
and the opportunities that
arise from those spaces.

00:53:15.470 --> 00:53:17.210
What do we do?

00:53:17.210 --> 00:53:23.360
And so I really want to
underscore for my community is

00:53:23.360 --> 00:53:31.280
I don't love how a lot of
times when we're talking

00:53:31.280 --> 00:53:35.850
about liberation, a
really popular approach

00:53:35.850 --> 00:53:38.900
is to approach
liberation from a really

00:53:38.900 --> 00:53:40.970
individualized perspective.

00:53:40.970 --> 00:53:44.620
So I often hear
people say, liberation

00:53:44.620 --> 00:53:47.240
is whatever it
feels like to you.

00:53:47.240 --> 00:53:49.790
Liberation is whatever--

00:53:49.790 --> 00:53:53.270
And I'm like, no.
[? I don't want. ?] Right?

00:53:53.270 --> 00:53:55.940
So one of the things that I
try to underscore in my work

00:53:55.940 --> 00:53:59.030
personally and the work
that we do For Harriet

00:53:59.030 --> 00:54:01.580
is to underscore that
pleasure is important.

00:54:01.580 --> 00:54:02.810
Pleasure is important.

00:54:02.810 --> 00:54:04.160
We are human beings.

00:54:04.160 --> 00:54:06.410
And it is important for
us to enjoy our lives

00:54:06.410 --> 00:54:07.730
while we're here.

00:54:07.730 --> 00:54:10.730
But I urge people to
interrogate those pleasures.

00:54:10.730 --> 00:54:14.420
I think joy is important.

00:54:14.420 --> 00:54:17.110
I live for my
five-year-old nieces.

00:54:17.110 --> 00:54:19.340
