01:06:17.890 --> 01:06:18.390
Yeah.

01:06:18.390 --> 01:06:19.880
It's before the Manifesto.

01:06:19.880 --> 01:06:22.760
And by the way, I didn't
know that work in 1999

01:06:22.760 --> 01:06:25.130
when I wrote the Manifesto.

01:06:25.130 --> 01:06:28.280
I met her around 2000, 2001.

01:06:28.280 --> 01:06:33.590
And so that's the idea that
we need to take the trans life

01:06:33.590 --> 01:06:36.560
and existence as given.

01:06:36.560 --> 01:06:38.100
It's for granted.

01:06:38.100 --> 01:06:40.030
We're not debating that.

01:06:40.030 --> 01:06:42.560
People exist, and we
don't need to have

01:06:42.560 --> 01:06:44.810
any theoretical
justification for that.

01:06:44.810 --> 01:06:46.070
People exist.

01:06:46.070 --> 01:06:48.140
And then talk about
what we need to make

01:06:48.140 --> 01:06:50.355
people's lives less horrible.

01:06:53.010 --> 01:06:55.490
But that doesn't
happen very much.

01:06:55.490 --> 01:06:58.340
We think that when we
respect someone's identity

01:06:58.340 --> 01:07:02.400
and we respect somebody's
principal pronouns, that's it.

01:07:02.400 --> 01:07:03.510
That's the end of it.

01:07:03.510 --> 01:07:07.280
And that's how the bar
for the being trans allies

01:07:07.280 --> 01:07:12.780
has been set so low, that just
by satisfying that, somehow you

01:07:12.780 --> 01:07:19.040
escape any further
requirement to do something,

01:07:19.040 --> 01:07:22.340
to address that kind of violence
and inequality and poverty

01:07:22.340 --> 01:07:25.150
all the things that affect
the people who are trans.

01:07:25.150 --> 01:07:27.650
And this is like a neoliberal
politics privilege [INAUDIBLE]

01:07:27.650 --> 01:07:32.900
individual liberty to identify
who they are, reduces gender

01:07:32.900 --> 01:07:35.030
to the individual preferences.

01:07:35.030 --> 01:07:37.790
But gender is not just
individual preferences.

01:07:37.790 --> 01:07:41.230
It's a [INAUDIBLE] social
stratification and violence as

01:07:41.230 --> 01:07:43.310
well as of resistance
and liberation.

01:07:43.310 --> 01:07:45.950
So that when you don't look at
that, when you think of it only

01:07:45.950 --> 01:07:49.070
as a label you put on yourself
and then other people just

01:07:49.070 --> 01:07:51.110
need to respect that,
that removes this

01:07:51.110 --> 01:07:54.005
from the social context where
people are actually living.

01:07:56.600 --> 01:08:01.550
The trans terms and
concepts are often

01:08:01.550 --> 01:08:06.260
defined in a removed,
anti-feminist, even,

01:08:06.260 --> 01:08:07.760
[? reactionary ?] ways.

01:08:07.760 --> 01:08:09.710
People define trans
as somebody who

01:08:09.710 --> 01:08:12.500
is born with a body
that's different from how

01:08:12.500 --> 01:08:13.550
they identify.

01:08:13.550 --> 01:08:17.359
And they say, well, the cis,
that's opposite of a trans,

01:08:17.359 --> 01:08:19.010
for those people who
haven't heard it.

01:08:19.010 --> 01:08:22.430
People often define cis means
that you are born with a body

01:08:22.430 --> 01:08:26.149
and you're fine with the gender
that you are assigned with.

01:08:26.149 --> 01:08:30.680
And if the being fine with the
gender you are assigned with

01:08:30.680 --> 01:08:35.000
was what makes you cis, this
then feminists are not cis.

01:08:35.000 --> 01:08:38.450
Feminists are not OK with the
kind of gender, the imposition

01:08:38.450 --> 01:08:41.300
of gender that's placed on us.

01:08:41.300 --> 01:08:46.850
And yet, that really
diminishes the reality

01:08:46.850 --> 01:08:48.290
that cis is actually real.

01:08:48.290 --> 01:08:51.710
Trans people do experience
a certain limitation

01:08:51.710 --> 01:08:53.359
and restriction in life.

01:08:53.359 --> 01:08:55.740
So it's a real thing that
we need to talk about.

01:08:55.740 --> 01:08:58.760
But by defining it in such
a [? reactionary ?] way,

01:08:58.760 --> 01:09:01.729
that it makes it lose meaning.

01:09:01.729 --> 01:09:05.210
So often it's just
really poorly defined.

01:09:05.210 --> 01:09:09.859
And this happens because we
remove the trans politics

01:09:09.859 --> 01:09:14.810
and transfeminism from
the realities of how

01:09:14.810 --> 01:09:18.529
people experience in our lives.

01:09:18.529 --> 01:09:23.149
But there was one time the
trans movement has actually

01:09:23.149 --> 01:09:27.680
gone more intersectional,
[? especially ?] in 2014.

01:09:27.680 --> 01:09:30.770
That's the year in
January [INAUDIBLE]

01:09:30.770 --> 01:09:32.460
was released from prison.

01:09:32.460 --> 01:09:36.920
She was a black trans women
who was put in the men's prison

01:09:36.920 --> 01:09:38.520
for defending herself.

01:09:38.520 --> 01:09:41.600
And then she when she came out,
she and the black trans women

01:09:41.600 --> 01:09:45.500
actress Laverne Cox,
went around in the media

01:09:45.500 --> 01:09:49.250
and around the country talking
about prison abolition, prison

01:09:49.250 --> 01:09:51.890
reform, prison
abolition, actually,

01:09:51.890 --> 01:09:53.420
talking about how
the prison is just

01:09:53.420 --> 01:09:57.140
not a good thing
for trans people

01:09:57.140 --> 01:10:00.450
and that we shouldn't just
be looking at the pronouns.

01:10:00.450 --> 01:10:03.020
We need to be thinking
about prisons.

01:10:03.020 --> 01:10:05.030
In February, Janet
Mock's book-- she's

01:10:05.030 --> 01:10:06.710
another black trans
women who's also

01:10:06.710 --> 01:10:11.030
mixed-race in Hawaii, an
indigenous Hawaiian woman,

01:10:11.030 --> 01:10:14.810
released the book, Redefining
Realness in February 2014.

01:10:14.810 --> 01:10:18.800
And in June, the Laverne Cox,
the black trans woman actress,

01:10:18.800 --> 01:10:21.740
was on the cover of Time
Magazine with the title

01:10:21.740 --> 01:10:23.700
The Transgender Tipping Point.

01:10:23.700 --> 01:10:27.500
And then in January
2015, we saw the release

01:10:27.500 --> 01:10:29.120
of the film The Tangerine.

01:10:29.120 --> 01:10:31.830
How many of you
have seen Tangerine?

01:10:31.830 --> 01:10:32.450
Watch it.

01:10:32.450 --> 01:10:34.810
It's [? the ?] best film.

01:10:34.810 --> 01:10:36.000
I love it.

01:10:36.000 --> 01:10:41.320
It's about the black
trans women who are doing

01:10:41.320 --> 01:10:43.230
sex work and all kinds of--

01:10:43.230 --> 01:10:47.157
their community and all the
crazy shit that happens.

01:10:47.157 --> 01:10:47.990
You should watch it.

01:10:47.990 --> 01:10:49.060
It's amazing.

01:10:49.060 --> 01:10:51.280
It's comedic.

01:10:51.280 --> 01:10:56.290
And it shows the trans women,
black trans women, characters

01:10:56.290 --> 01:10:59.920
as acted by black trans
women and beautiful.

01:10:59.920 --> 01:11:03.850
Anyway, there was a rush of
this focus on black trans women.

01:11:03.850 --> 01:11:06.100
And black trans women
somehow dominated

01:11:06.100 --> 01:11:10.420
the public representation of
a trans issues for a while.

01:11:10.420 --> 01:11:14.200
And it's not just
only the black trans

01:11:14.200 --> 01:11:15.960
women that were on the
cover of magazines.

01:11:15.960 --> 01:11:18.220
But they were talking
about prison abolition.

01:11:18.220 --> 01:11:20.440
And that has never
happened before.

01:11:20.440 --> 01:11:23.860
And then that dominance
of the black trans

01:11:23.860 --> 01:11:29.472
women in the media and all
that died down quickly in 2015.

01:11:29.472 --> 01:11:30.840
What happen in 2015?

01:11:30.840 --> 01:11:32.620
Do you know?

01:11:32.620 --> 01:11:36.130
2015, what happened
was Caitlyn Jenner.

01:11:36.130 --> 01:11:38.700
Caitlyn Jenner, who
supported Donald Trump.

01:11:38.700 --> 01:11:42.460
Caitlyn Jenner, who said
to the Vanity Fair magazine

01:11:42.460 --> 01:11:44.170
the hardest part
about being a woman

01:11:44.170 --> 01:11:46.330
is figuring out what to wear.

01:11:46.330 --> 01:11:52.450
So she became the face of the
transgender people in America.

01:11:52.450 --> 01:11:57.400
And along with that, we saw the
rise of the anti-trans bathroom

01:11:57.400 --> 01:11:58.876
bills around the country.

01:11:58.876 --> 01:12:01.000
So they're trying to restrict
trans people's access

01:12:01.000 --> 01:12:03.720
to bathrooms.

01:12:03.720 --> 01:12:06.060
So with all of those--

01:12:06.060 --> 01:12:09.810
and also I feel like both the
gay rights and anti-gay rights

01:12:09.810 --> 01:12:13.500
movements used the
bathroom issue because they

01:12:13.500 --> 01:12:15.810
lost the issue of marriage.

01:12:15.810 --> 01:12:18.330
The marriage was--
the Supreme Court,

01:12:18.330 --> 01:12:20.040
everything might come back.

01:12:20.040 --> 01:12:24.210
But for the moment, it
was resolved nationally.

01:12:24.210 --> 01:12:26.850
So they needed some issue
to rally around their people

01:12:26.850 --> 01:12:30.480
and raise more money so they
went to the bathroom issue

01:12:30.480 --> 01:12:31.770
on both sides.

01:12:31.770 --> 01:12:35.880
And how this bathroom
bill controversy happened

01:12:35.880 --> 01:12:39.450
was that it reduced-- the
whole idea of bathroom access

01:12:39.450 --> 01:12:42.750
is way more political than just
whether or not trans people can

01:12:42.750 --> 01:12:44.430
use the bathroom.

01:12:44.430 --> 01:12:46.830
We think about trans
inclusion, but we also

01:12:46.830 --> 01:12:51.240
think about the access for
homeless people and people

01:12:51.240 --> 01:12:53.250
using drugs in the
public bathrooms

01:12:53.250 --> 01:12:57.690
because there are no
other safe place to do so.

01:12:57.690 --> 01:13:02.340
The politics around racial
segregation was a thing.

01:13:02.340 --> 01:13:07.080
There is sexual violence,
sexual harassment in restrooms.

01:13:07.080 --> 01:13:09.870
The bathroom in
certain communities

01:13:09.870 --> 01:13:12.150
was the site for
cruising for sex.

01:13:12.150 --> 01:13:15.840
So there's lots of politics
and culture behind that.

01:13:15.840 --> 01:13:17.280
And then also we have--

01:13:17.280 --> 01:13:18.750
it's just so funny.

01:13:18.750 --> 01:13:21.870
So many cafes around
in Seattle where I live

01:13:21.870 --> 01:13:26.340
have a sign that says all are
welcome, immigrants welcome.

01:13:26.340 --> 01:13:28.910
And then bathroom
for customers only.

01:13:28.910 --> 01:13:30.410
No public bathroom.

01:13:30.410 --> 01:13:34.980
At the same-- next
to each other.

01:13:34.980 --> 01:13:39.540
And then when you think
about the establishment

01:13:39.540 --> 01:13:42.750
of quality-of-life crime
laws which makes it

01:13:42.750 --> 01:13:45.750
a crime for people to lie
down in the street or pee,

01:13:45.750 --> 01:13:48.410
urinate in the street
and things like that.

01:13:48.410 --> 01:13:51.570
And those are specifically
targeting certain communities.

01:13:51.570 --> 01:13:53.410
So there are so many
political things

01:13:53.410 --> 01:13:56.760
that are involved in this idea
about bathroom access itself.

01:13:56.760 --> 01:14:00.310
And yet it's just reduced
to who gets to access--

01:14:00.310 --> 01:14:02.492
which person gets to
access which bathroom?

01:14:02.492 --> 01:14:04.450
And they're not thinking
about homeless people.

01:14:04.450 --> 01:14:07.650
They're not thinking about
other people who are--

01:14:07.650 --> 01:14:10.710
people with disabilities
who can't access bathrooms.

01:14:10.710 --> 01:14:13.860
They're only thinking about
which white trans women can

01:14:13.860 --> 01:14:15.600
access women's restrooms.

01:14:15.600 --> 01:14:19.950
That's how reduced
that issue is.

01:14:19.950 --> 01:14:23.130
We need to not do this.

01:14:23.130 --> 01:14:24.940
We need to go back to the--

01:14:24.940 --> 01:14:29.220
oh, [? Adrie-- ?] we need to
think about the gender justice

01:14:29.220 --> 01:14:32.160
and gender liberation, not
the gender libertarianism,

01:14:32.160 --> 01:14:35.100
where you get to decide
which gender you are.

01:14:35.100 --> 01:14:40.050
We need the public spaces
reimagined radically,

01:14:40.050 --> 01:14:42.570
not just the
gender-appropriate bathrooms

01:14:42.570 --> 01:14:48.030
and designating the gender
policies for each facilities.

01:14:48.030 --> 01:14:49.800
And we need prison
abolition and not

01:14:49.800 --> 01:14:52.650
gender-sensitive prisons
that can put people

01:14:52.650 --> 01:14:53.850
in the right place.

01:14:53.850 --> 01:14:56.730
And I want to end with
that what [INAUDIBLE] said

01:14:56.730 --> 01:14:58.740
in the early interviews
right after she came out

01:14:58.740 --> 01:15:02.420
of prison, when she was put in
the men's prison for two years.

01:15:02.420 --> 01:15:06.330
And people lobbied,
organized to try to get her

01:15:06.330 --> 01:15:09.510
to be transferred
to a women's prison.

01:15:09.510 --> 01:15:11.940
But she actually
responded to that,

01:15:11.940 --> 01:15:14.370
saying that, no, the
women's prison is not

01:15:14.370 --> 01:15:16.650
an appropriate place
for me, either.

01:15:16.650 --> 01:15:20.610
There's no appropriate place
in a prison for a black trans

01:15:20.610 --> 01:15:23.250
women like her and
probably for nobody else.

01:15:23.250 --> 01:15:26.840
So she was telling the
people, and many of those

01:15:26.840 --> 01:15:29.557
are trans activists and
trans allies who are white,

01:15:29.557 --> 01:15:31.140
who don't know
anything about prison--

01:15:31.140 --> 01:15:33.150
I'm not saying that
white people don't know--

01:15:33.150 --> 01:15:34.890
I'm talking about
people who have

01:15:34.890 --> 01:15:37.890
no experience in
the prison activism

01:15:37.890 --> 01:15:41.820
before are being introduced
to that through the work

01:15:41.820 --> 01:15:45.330
of a black trans woman
who was in men's prison

01:15:45.330 --> 01:15:48.030
and telling people, rather
than to fight the fact that she

01:15:48.030 --> 01:15:50.840
was misclassified into men's
prison instead of women's

01:15:50.840 --> 01:15:54.210
prison, we need to fight
to release and free

01:15:54.210 --> 01:15:58.080
all trans women and all
black people and all people

01:15:58.080 --> 01:15:58.830
from the prisons.

01:15:58.830 --> 01:16:00.750
And so that's like a really--

01:16:00.750 --> 01:16:02.503
it was really--

01:16:02.503 --> 01:16:04.270
I don't know what to say.

01:16:04.270 --> 01:16:06.120
It was really
exciting to see that.

01:16:06.120 --> 01:16:11.940
And that became the call
of the trans movement

01:16:11.940 --> 01:16:14.900
for a second in 2014.

01:16:14.900 --> 01:16:17.310
I want to bring that back.

01:16:17.310 --> 01:16:18.070
OK.

01:16:18.070 --> 01:16:20.570
[APPLAUSE]

01:16:28.570 --> 01:16:29.260
- Wow.

01:16:29.260 --> 01:16:32.380
Thank you so much.

01:16:32.380 --> 01:16:34.420
It's interesting,
because one of the things

01:16:34.420 --> 01:16:37.902
about our generations is that
we spend so much time thinking--

01:16:37.902 --> 01:16:40.360
especially people who are maybe
a little bit older than you

01:16:40.360 --> 01:16:43.400
guys, like me-- that we
spent so much time thinking,

01:16:43.400 --> 01:16:45.880
oh, my gosh, we don't have
progressive intellectual life,

01:16:45.880 --> 01:16:48.520
progressive cultural life,
where has it happened?

01:16:48.520 --> 01:16:50.080
And it's just such
a pleasure to me

01:16:50.080 --> 01:16:52.270
personally to be able
to be here with you guys

01:16:52.270 --> 01:16:56.710
and to realize the amazing
work that you're doing

01:16:56.710 --> 01:16:58.510
and the amazing
energy that you all

01:16:58.510 --> 01:17:01.537
are bringing to your activism
and into your creative stuff.

01:17:01.537 --> 01:17:03.370
Fatimah, I wanted to
say to you thank you so

01:17:03.370 --> 01:17:05.580
much for your beautiful poetry.

01:17:05.580 --> 01:17:07.246
It was just, frankly, fantastic.

01:17:07.246 --> 01:17:09.134
[APPLAUSE]

01:17:12.220 --> 01:17:15.285
And just you know, I'm a super
snob about literature so--

01:17:15.285 --> 01:17:16.680
[LAUGHTER]

01:17:16.680 --> 01:17:17.610
You're good.

01:17:17.610 --> 01:17:19.470
You're good.

01:17:19.470 --> 01:17:21.780
And I just wanted
to say you had me,

01:17:21.780 --> 01:17:24.270
and I think you set the
tone for this conversation

01:17:24.270 --> 01:17:26.910
with that whole idea that
we don't want-- none of us

01:17:26.910 --> 01:17:29.450
wants our identities to
be thought of as just lack

01:17:29.450 --> 01:17:30.090
and trauma.

01:17:30.090 --> 01:17:33.600
All of us are unbelievably
complicated people.

01:17:33.600 --> 01:17:37.680
Dana, I love the
idea of the fact

01:17:37.680 --> 01:17:42.960
that young feminists, some of
them survivors, many of them

01:17:42.960 --> 01:17:45.990
survivors, are,
in fact, thinking

01:17:45.990 --> 01:17:48.660
in sophisticated ways
about holistic responses

01:17:48.660 --> 01:17:49.740
to sexual violence.

01:17:49.740 --> 01:17:51.619
That is an amazing
and brave thing.

01:17:51.619 --> 01:17:53.910
And you and the people that
you're doing your work with

01:17:53.910 --> 01:17:55.020
need to be commended.

01:17:55.020 --> 01:17:57.300
And I told you
earlier that I think

01:17:57.300 --> 01:17:59.130
that the fact that
you have been involved

01:17:59.130 --> 01:18:01.100
in an organization
of young people--

01:18:01.100 --> 01:18:04.890
and training young people to
take over the organization

01:18:04.890 --> 01:18:07.230
is an incredibly radical
thing to be doing,

01:18:07.230 --> 01:18:09.025
radical in the best
sense of the word.

01:18:09.025 --> 01:18:11.720
So thank you for that.

01:18:11.720 --> 01:18:14.360
And Melissa, for
one thing, I wanted

01:18:14.360 --> 01:18:19.200
to tell you that my
first-ever album was Queen

01:18:19.200 --> 01:18:21.390
and my second ever album
I ever bought on my own

01:18:21.390 --> 01:18:22.900
was Holly Near.

01:18:22.900 --> 01:18:25.046
So I'm right there
with you on that.

01:18:25.046 --> 01:18:26.670
And I still have that
Holly Near album.

01:18:26.670 --> 01:18:28.560
And I got it signed by
Holly Near, no less.

01:18:28.560 --> 01:18:32.220
And so I think that it's amazing
to have a generation of people

01:18:32.220 --> 01:18:36.060
that's having a set of
cultural references built off

01:18:36.060 --> 01:18:37.351
of feminism.

01:18:37.351 --> 01:18:38.850
And thank you for
that conversation.

01:18:38.850 --> 01:18:40.800
And I love it that
right at the beginning

01:18:40.800 --> 01:18:42.900
of the process of
VIDA's development

01:18:42.900 --> 01:18:45.690
you all were already
interested intersectionality.

01:18:45.690 --> 01:18:51.382
So it was a question of
the genders of the writers

01:18:51.382 --> 01:18:53.340
and the creative people
who were being included

01:18:53.340 --> 01:18:55.470
but also their race
and their sexuality

01:18:55.470 --> 01:18:59.310
and their age and their
ability or disability.

01:18:59.310 --> 01:19:03.400
And then Melissa, I have
to say, excuse me, Kim,

01:19:03.400 --> 01:19:05.290
I have to say to you that--

01:19:05.290 --> 01:19:08.140
to thank you, actually,
because, in fact,

01:19:08.140 --> 01:19:10.290
this is my second
week at Harvard.

01:19:10.290 --> 01:19:15.000
And so I was like, well,
there is a robust community

01:19:15.000 --> 01:19:16.700
of black women.

01:19:16.700 --> 01:19:18.630
There is plenty of
feminist theory.

01:19:18.630 --> 01:19:20.820
And there's both
women and gender

01:19:20.820 --> 01:19:23.410
studies and African and
African-American studies.

01:19:23.410 --> 01:19:25.050
So I'm psyched all up.

01:19:25.050 --> 01:19:26.460
I'm psyched all up about it.

01:19:26.460 --> 01:19:27.420
- You're welcome.

01:19:27.420 --> 01:19:29.700
- Thank you very much.

01:19:29.700 --> 01:19:33.390
And I couldn't
agree with you more

01:19:33.390 --> 01:19:36.690
that we need to do better
citational practice.

01:19:36.690 --> 01:19:39.920
And I'm a snob about
citational practice, in fact.

01:19:39.920 --> 01:19:41.800
I, in fact, know what
I'm talking about.

01:19:41.800 --> 01:19:43.290
And I think that
it's a point that

01:19:43.290 --> 01:19:46.800
has to be driven home over
and over and over again.

01:19:46.800 --> 01:19:50.522
And I really like this idea
of what does feminist life

01:19:50.522 --> 01:19:52.980
actually look like and what
does a feminist future actually

01:19:52.980 --> 01:19:53.479
look like?

01:19:53.479 --> 01:19:55.230
And I'll go through
this quickly,

01:19:55.230 --> 01:19:58.830
and then I'll ask all of
you this question exactly.

01:19:58.830 --> 01:20:00.660
And Emi, obviously,
your comments

01:20:00.660 --> 01:20:05.324
were so informative
and so brave.

01:20:05.324 --> 01:20:07.740
It's rare that you have somebody
talk about their own work

01:20:07.740 --> 01:20:09.992
and say, you know, this
work that I did 20 years ago

01:20:09.992 --> 01:20:12.450
actually has its own limitations
that are based on the fact

01:20:12.450 --> 01:20:15.190
that it was done 20 years ago.

01:20:15.190 --> 01:20:17.910
And I bet you're a rougher
reader of your work

01:20:17.910 --> 01:20:20.190
than everybody else is.

01:20:20.190 --> 01:20:22.650
And then it's a bold
statement to say

01:20:22.650 --> 01:20:27.120
that you believe that there's
too much emphasis on questions

01:20:27.120 --> 01:20:30.445
of individual identities
and that what you believed

01:20:30.445 --> 01:20:32.070
should happen, I
think, a lot of people

01:20:32.070 --> 01:20:34.140
actually believe is-- the
phrase that you've said

01:20:34.140 --> 01:20:39.960
is the public spaces should
be reimagined radically.

01:20:39.960 --> 01:20:44.610
So I was stunned by what
you were saying, all of you.

01:20:44.610 --> 01:20:49.260
But what kills me, what really
I can't get my head around,

01:20:49.260 --> 01:20:52.110
is that we're here with
a group of very, very

01:20:52.110 --> 01:20:53.970
impressive persons.

01:20:53.970 --> 01:20:57.870
And [INAUDIBLE] are doing
all sorts of fantastic work.

01:20:57.870 --> 01:21:02.400
I don't get it, how you can
have this community of people

01:21:02.400 --> 01:21:04.540
engaging with this
community of people

01:21:04.540 --> 01:21:06.150
and yet we're in a
time in our country

01:21:06.150 --> 01:21:10.860
in which intersectional is
wildly under attack, when

01:21:10.860 --> 01:21:13.470
there's a certain set
of identity politics

01:21:13.470 --> 01:21:15.200
that have taken
over the government.

01:21:15.200 --> 01:21:18.840
And so can you explain to us
how that weird bifurcation

01:21:18.840 --> 01:21:20.670
is happening in our culture?

01:21:20.670 --> 01:21:23.268
And then tell us
the way forward.

01:21:23.268 --> 01:21:25.140
[LAUGHTER]

01:21:26.330 --> 01:21:28.580
But I also should say that
we don't have so much time.

01:21:28.580 --> 01:21:30.454
So you're going to need
to be quick about it,

01:21:30.454 --> 01:21:34.240
because we want to have
questions and answer, too.

01:21:34.240 --> 01:21:36.800
- I would say that
pushback is to be expected.

01:21:36.800 --> 01:21:37.750
I'm not a historian.

01:21:37.750 --> 01:21:39.360
But I do be reading.

01:21:39.360 --> 01:21:44.680
And I got a degree in African
and African-American studies.

01:21:44.680 --> 01:21:47.350
Shout out to [INAUDIBLE]
[? Skip ?] [? Gates. ?] So

01:21:47.350 --> 01:21:50.320
anyways, I think we see
throughout history that

01:21:50.320 --> 01:21:54.137
as people of color, marginalized
people make inroads.

01:21:54.137 --> 01:21:56.470
There's always going to be
pushback from the mainstream,

01:21:56.470 --> 01:21:57.970
from majority.

01:21:57.970 --> 01:22:06.340
That power shift always causes
a mass revolt and pushback.

01:22:06.340 --> 01:22:10.150
And so I'm not
necessarily surprised.

01:22:10.150 --> 01:22:13.720
I heard an amazing writer
called [? Doreen ?] [? St. ?]

01:22:13.720 --> 01:22:14.740
[? Felix ?] once.

01:22:14.740 --> 01:22:17.200
She said that this
is just evidence

01:22:17.200 --> 01:22:19.429
that white supremacy
is on its last breath,

01:22:19.429 --> 01:22:20.470
you know what I'm saying.

01:22:20.470 --> 01:22:23.170
So this historical
moment that we're in,

01:22:23.170 --> 01:22:26.110
I don't consider it
to be a huge failure.

01:22:26.110 --> 01:22:31.025
I consider it to be evidence
that we are on the right path.

01:22:31.025 --> 01:22:33.450
[APPLAUSE]

01:22:37.330 --> 01:22:39.520
- Can I ask you guys
back about that.

01:22:39.520 --> 01:22:42.160
I tend to think
that that's true.

01:22:42.160 --> 01:22:46.600
At the same time, what
about the question of people

01:22:46.600 --> 01:22:50.290
right now in having to
deal with backlash in ways

01:22:50.290 --> 01:22:51.880
that are quite deadly?

01:22:51.880 --> 01:22:54.650
What do you say to communities
that really are getting it

01:22:54.650 --> 01:22:55.480
in the neck?

01:22:55.480 --> 01:22:57.610
There's lots of
[? spikes ?] of all types

01:22:57.610 --> 01:22:58.810
of violence in this society.

01:22:58.810 --> 01:23:00.190
How do we actually--

01:23:00.190 --> 01:23:03.400
I agree that we're probably
moving ahead historically.

01:23:03.400 --> 01:23:07.000
How do we care for each other
during what are very, very

01:23:07.000 --> 01:23:08.523
difficult times for all of us?

01:23:13.360 --> 01:23:14.600
I also will call on you.

01:23:14.600 --> 01:23:15.680
I am a professor.

01:23:19.890 --> 01:23:22.731
- I can't-- does this mic work?

01:23:22.731 --> 01:23:23.230
No.

01:23:23.230 --> 01:23:24.340
Yes.

01:23:24.340 --> 01:23:27.540
So I think-- this is hard for
me because I'm not an academic,

01:23:27.540 --> 01:23:28.540
I'm not an intellectual.

01:23:28.540 --> 01:23:29.902
I'm an artist.

01:23:29.902 --> 01:23:31.360
So all of my work
is contextualized

01:23:31.360 --> 01:23:36.700
by the practice of art making
and by being an artist first.

01:23:36.700 --> 01:23:41.830
And so thinking about the
kind of current age we're in,

01:23:41.830 --> 01:23:44.440
I agree a lot with
Kim about the feeling

01:23:44.440 --> 01:23:53.260
of this moment being a
response to the kind of hope

01:23:53.260 --> 01:23:56.500
that folks had when Obama
was president and when folks

01:23:56.500 --> 01:23:59.830
were like, oh, now
we're post-racial

01:23:59.830 --> 01:24:01.990
or whatever that mass was.

01:24:01.990 --> 01:24:06.640
But I think that as an
artist, though, we've been--

01:24:06.640 --> 01:24:08.229
what you do is--

01:24:08.229 --> 01:24:08.770
I don't know.

01:24:08.770 --> 01:24:09.580
Whatever.

01:24:09.580 --> 01:24:11.410
I've seen the ways
in which folks have

01:24:11.410 --> 01:24:13.630
been suffering for forever.

01:24:13.630 --> 01:24:14.900
This isn't to me--

01:24:14.900 --> 01:24:18.740
and a lot of folks have asked
me when the book was coming out,

01:24:18.740 --> 01:24:20.950
when Brown Girls was coming
out, I was like, well,

01:24:20.950 --> 01:24:21.940
now's the time.

01:24:21.940 --> 01:24:24.100
And I was like, now
is the time for what?

01:24:24.100 --> 01:24:25.210
That's been happening.

01:24:25.210 --> 01:24:26.230
This has been happening.

01:24:26.230 --> 01:24:29.110
You read articles
from the '70s and '80s

01:24:29.110 --> 01:24:32.260
of cops murdering young
black people in New York

01:24:32.260 --> 01:24:34.310
and all over the country.

01:24:34.310 --> 01:24:37.060
This is not-- all of
this stuff has just kind

01:24:37.060 --> 01:24:38.620
of been happening for so long.

01:24:38.620 --> 01:24:40.450
And it's really,
really frustrating

01:24:40.450 --> 01:24:44.440
to feel like that has
continued to happen

01:24:44.440 --> 01:24:47.890
and people's labor has continued
to happen around organizing

01:24:47.890 --> 01:24:49.430
and being activists around it.

01:24:49.430 --> 01:24:53.530
And then there is still such
daunting white supremacy.

01:24:53.530 --> 01:24:55.330
That's a really
frustrating thing.

01:24:55.330 --> 01:24:59.110
And to me, what I think
about it as an artist,

01:24:59.110 --> 01:25:01.204
what is the role of art in that?

01:25:01.204 --> 01:25:02.620
What is the role
of things that we

01:25:02.620 --> 01:25:06.220
can do as artists to
both provide spaces

01:25:06.220 --> 01:25:08.440
of alleviation and
of joy and also

01:25:08.440 --> 01:25:11.061
to provide spaces of a
magnifying glass and a witness

01:25:11.061 --> 01:25:11.560
to that?

01:25:11.560 --> 01:25:14.620
And so that to me
is what I think

01:25:14.620 --> 01:25:16.570
of as the responsibility
of an artist

01:25:16.570 --> 01:25:21.280
is to say how can you
both be the magnifying

01:25:21.280 --> 01:25:26.660
glass and the moments where
you can kind of build a shelter

01:25:26.660 --> 01:25:30.220
for that feeling?

01:25:30.220 --> 01:25:33.790
And I agree a lot with
Emi about the kind of ways

01:25:33.790 --> 01:25:35.860
that it's really important
to radically reimagine

01:25:35.860 --> 01:25:36.640
public spaces.

01:25:36.640 --> 01:25:40.660
And I think that if there were
spaces in which we could have

01:25:40.660 --> 01:25:43.210
public reckonings
with our history,

01:25:43.210 --> 01:25:45.730
if there were spaces in
which that was named,

01:25:45.730 --> 01:25:48.320
I think we would live in
a really different world.

01:25:48.320 --> 01:25:51.790
And I think that
if we really had

01:25:51.790 --> 01:25:57.280
to grapple where we walked on
a day-to-day basis, the things

01:25:57.280 --> 01:25:59.230
that have happened in
the spaces we're around,

01:25:59.230 --> 01:26:00.790
I think we would
just really live

01:26:00.790 --> 01:26:01.956
in a really different world.

01:26:01.956 --> 01:26:03.820
- So are you saying
that we should

01:26:03.820 --> 01:26:08.740
do more monuments, more memorial
practices in the society

01:26:08.740 --> 01:26:10.180
at large?

01:26:10.180 --> 01:26:10.729
- I think so.

01:26:10.729 --> 01:26:11.520
I mean, I think so.

01:26:11.520 --> 01:26:13.660
I think that--

01:26:13.660 --> 01:26:16.900
I did a Fullbright
in Bosnia where--

01:26:16.900 --> 01:26:20.110
and it was 20 years after
the siege of Sarajevo.

01:26:20.110 --> 01:26:22.150
And I was really interested
in the ways that--

01:26:22.150 --> 01:26:24.870
I was looking particularly
at memorialization,

01:26:24.870 --> 01:26:28.760
using art as a way of
memorializing violence.

01:26:28.760 --> 01:26:31.116
And I think what I saw there.

01:26:31.116 --> 01:26:31.990
And it's not perfect.

01:26:31.990 --> 01:26:33.940
But what I saw was
moments in which

01:26:33.940 --> 01:26:36.610
both through ephemeral
site-specific work

01:26:36.610 --> 01:26:40.180
and through monuments
and through art,

01:26:40.180 --> 01:26:42.460
and even just how
all the parks were

01:26:42.460 --> 01:26:44.770
converted into grave
sites out of necessity.

01:26:44.770 --> 01:26:48.160
There is a way when that
happens, you really grapple

01:26:48.160 --> 01:26:48.660
with things.

01:26:48.660 --> 01:26:51.402
And here, I think a
lot of American society

01:26:51.402 --> 01:26:53.860
is just really interested in
the Band-Aid and the cover-up.

01:26:53.860 --> 01:26:55.964
And I don't think that
that's a good thing.

01:26:55.964 --> 01:26:57.880
- Can I ask all of you
a question that follows

01:26:57.880 --> 01:27:00.004
from that, then, about--

01:27:00.004 --> 01:27:02.170
especially because we're
talking about feminisms now

01:27:02.170 --> 01:27:07.660
and we're talking about
millennial feminism in relation

01:27:07.660 --> 01:27:09.310
to second-wave feminism--

01:27:09.310 --> 01:27:11.980
how is it that
you do as feminist

01:27:11.980 --> 01:27:14.710
the types of
understanding what has

01:27:14.710 --> 01:27:18.290
come before the types
of memorialization

01:27:18.290 --> 01:27:22.250
of previous ways of thinking
that actually can get

01:27:22.250 --> 01:27:24.250
to large amounts of people,
that actually allows

01:27:24.250 --> 01:27:25.600
us to not always be--

01:27:25.600 --> 01:27:28.570
every one of you said something
about recreating the wheel.

01:27:28.570 --> 01:27:31.180
And I'm not sure, as an
educator, that I know

01:27:31.180 --> 01:27:32.530
how to not recreate the wheel.

01:27:32.530 --> 01:27:34.238
I wonder if you guys
have ideas about how

01:27:34.238 --> 01:27:36.470
to do a better job of that.

01:27:40.150 --> 01:27:42.760
- I guess I will say--

01:27:42.760 --> 01:27:44.440
and I'll also relate
this back to art,

01:27:44.440 --> 01:27:46.960
because it's analogous for
something that comes up

01:27:46.960 --> 01:27:51.610
in my teaching a lot, which
is that I get a lot of writers

01:27:51.610 --> 01:27:54.100
being worried that
their work is going

01:27:54.100 --> 01:27:57.670
to be reinventing the wheel or
that it's not totally unique.

01:27:57.670 --> 01:28:00.910
And my answer to that
over the years has become,

01:28:00.910 --> 01:28:02.620
it doesn't have to be.

01:28:02.620 --> 01:28:04.990
Certainly there
is a way that you

01:28:04.990 --> 01:28:08.140
are creating a work that could
be executed and delivered

01:28:08.140 --> 01:28:10.780
in only the way that you
could possibly do that.

01:28:10.780 --> 01:28:12.720
But its message is not
going to be a new one,

01:28:12.720 --> 01:28:15.047
because the things that
we need to see in art,

01:28:15.047 --> 01:28:17.380
as the things that we need
to address with our activism,

01:28:17.380 --> 01:28:19.210
are not new problems.

01:28:19.210 --> 01:28:22.420
So I'm really into
Kimberley's phrase

01:28:22.420 --> 01:28:24.440
of robust citational practice.

01:28:24.440 --> 01:28:27.289
So I think it's not--

01:28:27.289 --> 01:28:29.830
I don't think there's a problem
with fighting the same fight.

01:28:29.830 --> 01:28:32.032
Because we haven't won it yet.

01:28:32.032 --> 01:28:34.240
It's about sort of giving
credit to the people who've

01:28:34.240 --> 01:28:38.200
done it before and to adopting
correct strategies that

01:28:38.200 --> 01:28:39.651
worked and didn't work.

01:28:39.651 --> 01:28:40.150
- All right.

01:28:40.150 --> 01:28:41.739
I'll ask one last
question on my own,

01:28:41.739 --> 01:28:43.780
and then I think that we
have the microphone here

01:28:43.780 --> 01:28:46.030
so we'll take some
questions from the audience.

01:28:46.030 --> 01:28:48.530
So I get all that.

01:28:48.530 --> 01:28:52.570
But how do you stay
robust yourselves?

01:28:52.570 --> 01:28:55.660
It's an amazing thing to have
a robust citational practice.

01:28:55.660 --> 01:28:58.220
It's an amazing thing to be
constantly doing your work.

01:28:58.220 --> 01:29:02.770
But how do you make sure
that our communities

01:29:02.770 --> 01:29:06.530
are caring for themselves and
in the fight for the long term?

01:29:06.530 --> 01:29:10.850
I like the idea of you've got to
have pleasure in life as well.

01:29:10.850 --> 01:29:13.949
And we all know that one of the
real tragedies of generations

01:29:13.949 --> 01:29:16.240
of activists who came before
us is that so many of them

01:29:16.240 --> 01:29:19.930
burned out, died early deaths,
had real financial problems,

01:29:19.930 --> 01:29:22.460
had real substance
problems, everything.

01:29:22.460 --> 01:29:26.987
So we would be wrong to not
note that and to try to say,

01:29:26.987 --> 01:29:29.320
at least among ourselves,
look, these are the strategies

01:29:29.320 --> 01:29:32.560
that one needs in order
to be an activist who

01:29:32.560 --> 01:29:36.240
is a robust activist
and a robust person.

01:29:36.240 --> 01:29:37.190
- Yeah.

01:29:37.190 --> 01:29:43.330
I would recall what
Fatimah said about lack.

01:29:43.330 --> 01:29:46.780
And what I see is its
converse, which is abundance

01:29:46.780 --> 01:29:49.660
and gratitude and
joy and plenty.

01:29:49.660 --> 01:29:53.410
And even in the midst of all
of these recurrent problems,

01:29:53.410 --> 01:29:54.280
we all have that.

01:29:54.280 --> 01:29:56.200
And I think most of
us referenced it.

01:29:56.200 --> 01:30:00.189
And for me, I have to
feed that part of me that

01:30:00.189 --> 01:30:01.480
is in touch with the abundance.

01:30:01.480 --> 01:30:03.940
And that comes from
absorbing other people's art.

01:30:03.940 --> 01:30:05.590
I talk about
therapy as much as I

01:30:05.590 --> 01:30:08.350
can because it has been
so necessary to my art

01:30:08.350 --> 01:30:13.010
and my activism and my
recovery and remaining robust.

01:30:13.010 --> 01:30:16.300
And I think that talking
about self-care--

01:30:16.300 --> 01:30:19.090
the term has a little
fatigued with that.

01:30:19.090 --> 01:30:20.674
But there are forms
of wellness that I

01:30:20.674 --> 01:30:22.923
think are radical, especially
for certain populations.

01:30:22.923 --> 01:30:24.430
- I loved in
Fatimah's second poem,

01:30:24.430 --> 01:30:28.920
I think it was, how to not get--

01:30:28.920 --> 01:30:30.261
what was it?

01:30:30.261 --> 01:30:31.155
- Hypothermia.

01:30:31.155 --> 01:30:32.049
- Ever so sorry.

01:30:32.049 --> 01:30:32.950
- Oh, that's OK.

01:30:32.950 --> 01:30:36.160
- That the answer to that
was have your friends.

01:30:36.160 --> 01:30:38.500
So self-care is also
about communities

01:30:38.500 --> 01:30:41.350
caring for each other
and caring for each other

01:30:41.350 --> 01:30:43.080
across differences as well.

01:30:43.080 --> 01:30:45.130
- I also just want
to say really fast

01:30:45.130 --> 01:30:48.730
that when I emphasize
to people my age

01:30:48.730 --> 01:30:51.130
and younger generations
of women that we don't

01:30:51.130 --> 01:30:53.950
have to recreate the wheel,
it is not necessarily

01:30:53.950 --> 01:30:55.945
an admonishment.

01:30:55.945 --> 01:30:58.570
It's the fact that-- look at all
of this incredible work that's

01:30:58.570 --> 01:30:59.410
been done.

01:30:59.410 --> 01:31:01.060
Look at this
incredible foundation

01:31:01.060 --> 01:31:02.579
that we have to build from.

01:31:02.579 --> 01:31:04.370
And then we don't have
to beat ourselves up

01:31:04.370 --> 01:31:06.610
if we don't feel like we
have all of the answers.

01:31:06.610 --> 01:31:08.710
And we don't have
to waste time trying

01:31:08.710 --> 01:31:12.250
to retread these arguments
that have already been had,

01:31:12.250 --> 01:31:16.250
trying to remake this theory
that's already been done.

01:31:16.250 --> 01:31:18.700
We get to remix and remake.

01:31:18.700 --> 01:31:22.330
And that's an
enormous opportunity.

01:31:22.330 --> 01:31:23.680
She mentioned abundance.

01:31:23.680 --> 01:31:26.121
I feel enormous gratitude
that we have that.

01:31:26.121 --> 01:31:26.620
- Right.

01:31:26.620 --> 01:31:28.300
That's fantastic.

01:31:28.300 --> 01:31:31.570
So I think that we can
take a few questions.

01:31:31.570 --> 01:31:34.334
I have been asked to
be that time police.

01:31:34.334 --> 01:31:35.000
I don't like it.

01:31:35.000 --> 01:31:39.300
I don't even believe in the
Western concept of time.

01:31:39.300 --> 01:31:41.880
But I will knuckle under
for the time being.

01:31:41.880 --> 01:31:44.560
If there are people who
would like to come to this

01:31:44.560 --> 01:31:47.800
mic in the center, if
you'd like to ask questions

01:31:47.800 --> 01:31:48.700
to our panelists.

