rest of the panel,

01:45:21.700 --> 01:45:25.150
but specifically looking
at some of the women that

01:45:25.150 --> 01:45:28.210
are in our community
who may not specifically

01:45:28.210 --> 01:45:32.450
identify with the word
feminist or feminism

01:45:32.450 --> 01:45:37.900
but practice it in action
every day in their community.

01:45:37.900 --> 01:45:41.230
And what we've been running
into over this last year

01:45:41.230 --> 01:45:46.940
is how to connect those
35-plus women of color

01:45:46.940 --> 01:45:51.580
with the new wave of young
academic students who

01:45:51.580 --> 01:45:55.770
want to hold space with them and
help them resolve their issues

01:45:55.770 --> 01:45:58.980
but do not necessarily--
the younger feminists

01:45:58.980 --> 01:46:03.790
are not identifying with the
older feminists in their work.

01:46:03.790 --> 01:46:07.600
And when you were talking about
dialogue between generations,

01:46:07.600 --> 01:46:08.710
how do we connect?

01:46:08.710 --> 01:46:11.060
What are some of the
best practices, Kimberly,

01:46:11.060 --> 01:46:15.730
you can advise our
organization and connecting

01:46:15.730 --> 01:46:20.440
an arc between those
generational understanding

01:46:20.440 --> 01:46:23.214
of what feminism is
for women of color?

01:46:23.214 --> 01:46:24.880
Sorry for that being
a lengthy question.

01:46:24.880 --> 01:46:25.379
- Sure.

01:46:25.379 --> 01:46:28.010
So I'll make it as
quick as possible.

01:46:28.010 --> 01:46:31.990
So I think that there are--

01:46:31.990 --> 01:46:33.490
black women are not a monolith.

01:46:33.490 --> 01:46:36.040
But there are certain
sorts of experiences

01:46:36.040 --> 01:46:38.560
that we can all connect to.

01:46:38.560 --> 01:46:45.790
So most black women can identify
with feeling undervalued

01:46:45.790 --> 01:46:49.210
by their employer or--

01:46:49.210 --> 01:46:51.370
and this is just
from my experience

01:46:51.370 --> 01:46:54.880
and from reading lots and lots
of black feminists texts--

01:46:54.880 --> 01:46:58.240
we can identify with a
certain marginalization

01:46:58.240 --> 01:46:58.990
in the workplace.

01:46:58.990 --> 01:47:01.270
We can identify with
feeling disempowered

01:47:01.270 --> 01:47:03.250
in our romantic relationships.

01:47:03.250 --> 01:47:05.050
We can identify
with feeling like we

01:47:05.050 --> 01:47:10.330
are [? mules ?] in our
interpersonal relationships,

01:47:10.330 --> 01:47:12.130
in our familial dynamics.

01:47:12.130 --> 01:47:15.520
I think that there are just
certain sorts of experiences

01:47:15.520 --> 01:47:20.740
that cross generations, that
cross socioeconomic status.

01:47:20.740 --> 01:47:26.309
The details of my
employer at my law firm

01:47:26.309 --> 01:47:27.850
is going to be
different from the way

01:47:27.850 --> 01:47:32.410
that your employer at your
restaurant job or service work

01:47:32.410 --> 01:47:33.130
job--

01:47:33.130 --> 01:47:35.590
the details of that stuff
is going to be different.

01:47:35.590 --> 01:47:38.680
But those underlying feelings,
we can connect there.

01:47:38.680 --> 01:47:41.560
And I think offering
people an open platform

01:47:41.560 --> 01:47:44.080
to talk about those
experiences, the foundations

01:47:44.080 --> 01:47:46.720
of those experiences,
and then get

01:47:46.720 --> 01:47:52.570
into the intricacies of the
differences, the detail,

01:47:52.570 --> 01:47:56.140
the dynamics, I think,
offers an opportunity

01:47:56.140 --> 01:47:58.090
to have connection there.

01:47:58.090 --> 01:48:01.810
I think that there's really
power in embracing difference.

01:48:01.810 --> 01:48:04.630
And so I wouldn't
be afraid of the way

01:48:04.630 --> 01:48:09.580
that those differences pop
up across our experiences.

01:48:09.580 --> 01:48:12.280
- On that note, I want
to take the opportunity

01:48:12.280 --> 01:48:15.630
to thank our fantastic
five panelists for a really

01:48:15.630 --> 01:48:16.230
remarkable--

01:48:16.230 --> 01:48:18.980
[APPLAUSE]

